46static_assert(std::is_trivially_copyable_v<QCalendar::YearMonthDay>);
47
48static inline QDate fixedDate(QCalendar::YearMonthDay parts, QCalendar cal)
49{
50 if ((parts.year < 0 && !cal.isProleptic()) || (parts.year == 0 && !cal.hasYearZero()))
51 return QDate();
52
53 parts.day = qMin(a: parts.day, b: cal.daysInMonth(month: parts.month, year: parts.year));
54 return cal.dateFromParts(parts);
55}
56
57static inline QDate fixedDate(QCalendar::YearMonthDay parts)
58{
59 if (parts.year) {
60 parts.day = qMin(a: parts.day, b: QGregorianCalendar::monthLength(month: parts.month, year: parts.year));
61 qint64 jd;
62 if (QGregorianCalendar::julianFromParts(year: parts.year, month: parts.month, day: parts.day, jd: &jd))
63 return QDate::fromJulianDay(jd_: jd);
64 }
65 return QDate();
66}

72#if QT_CONFIG(textdate)
73static const char qt_shortMonthNames[][4] = {
74 "Jan", "Feb", "Mar", "Apr", "May", "Jun",
75 "Jul", "Aug", "Sep", "Oct", "Nov", "Dec"
76};

78static int fromShortMonthName(QStringView monthName)
79{
80 for (unsigned int i = 0; i < sizeof(qt_shortMonthNames) / sizeof(qt_shortMonthNames[0]); ++i) {
81 if (monthName == QLatin1StringView(qt_shortMonthNames[i], 3))
82 return i + 1;
83 }
84 return -1;
85}

88#if QT_CONFIG(datestring) // depends on, so implies, textdate
89struct ParsedRfcDateTime {
90 QDate date;
91 QTime time;
92 int utcOffset;
93};
94
95static int shortDayFromName(QStringView name)
96{
97 const char16_t shortDayNames[] = u"MonTueWedThuFriSatSun";
98 for (int i = 0; i < 7; i++) {
99 if (name == QStringView(shortDayNames + 3 * i, 3))
100 return i + 1;
101 }
102 return 0;
103}
104
105static ParsedRfcDateTime rfcDateImpl(QStringView s)
106{
107 // Matches "[ddd,] dd MMM yyyy[ hh:mm[:ss]] [±hhmm]" - correct RFC 822, 2822, 5322 format -
108 // or "ddd MMM dd[ hh:mm:ss] yyyy [±hhmm]" - permissive RFC 850, 1036 (read only)
109 ParsedRfcDateTime result;
110
111 QVarLengthArray<QStringView, 6> words;
112
113 auto tokens = s.tokenize(needle: u' ', flags: Qt::SkipEmptyParts);
114 auto it = tokens.begin();
115 for (int i = 0; i < 6 && it != tokens.end(); ++i, ++it)
116 words.emplace_back(args: *it);
117
118 if (words.size() < 3 || it != tokens.end())
119 return result;
120 const QChar colon(u':');
121 bool ok = true;
122 QDate date;
123
124 const auto isShortName = [](QStringView name) {
125 return (name.size() == 3 && name[0].isUpper()
126 && name[1].isLower() && name[2].isLower());
127 };
128
129 /* Reject entirely (return) if the string is malformed; however, if the date
130 * is merely invalid, (break, so as to) go on to parsing of the time.
131 */
132 int yearIndex;
133 do { // "loop" so that we can use break on merely invalid, but "right shape" date.
134 QStringView dayName;
135 bool rfcX22 = true;
136 const QStringView maybeDayName = words.front();
137 if (maybeDayName.endsWith(c: u',')) {
138 dayName = maybeDayName.chopped(n: 1);
139 words.erase(pos: words.begin());
140 } else if (!maybeDayName.front().isDigit()) {
141 dayName = maybeDayName;
142 words.erase(pos: words.begin());
143 rfcX22 = false;
144 } // else: dayName is not specified (so we can only be RFC *22)
145 if (words.size() < 3 || words.size() > 5)
146 return result;
147
148 // Don't break before setting yearIndex.
149 int dayIndex, monthIndex;
150 if (rfcX22) {
151 // dd MMM yyyy [hh:mm[:ss]] [±hhmm]
152 dayIndex = 0;
153 monthIndex = 1;
154 yearIndex = 2;
155 } else {
156 // MMM dd[ hh:mm:ss] yyyy [±hhmm]
157 dayIndex = 1;
158 monthIndex = 0;
159 yearIndex = words.size() > 3 && words.at(idx: 2).contains(c: colon) ? 3 : 2;
160 }
161
162 int dayOfWeek = 0;
163 if (!dayName.isEmpty()) {
164 if (!isShortName(dayName))
165 return result;
166 dayOfWeek = shortDayFromName(name: dayName);
167 if (!dayOfWeek)
168 break;
169 }
170
171 const int day = words.at(idx: dayIndex).toInt(ok: &ok);
172 if (!ok)
173 return result;
174 const int year = words.at(idx: yearIndex).toInt(ok: &ok);
175 if (!ok)
176 return result;
177 const QStringView monthName = words.at(idx: monthIndex);
178 if (!isShortName(monthName))
179 return result;
180 int month = fromShortMonthName(monthName);
181 if (month < 0)
182 break;
183
184 date = QDate(year, month, day);
185 if (dayOfWeek && date.dayOfWeek() != dayOfWeek)
186 date = QDate();
187 } while (false);
188 words.remove(i: yearIndex);
189 words.remove(i: 0, n: 2); // month and day-of-month, in some order
190
191 // Time: [hh:mm[:ss]]
192 QTime time;
193 if (words.size() && words.at(idx: 0).contains(c: colon)) {
194 const QStringView when = words.front();
195 words.erase(pos: words.begin());
196 if (when.size() < 5 || when[2] != colon
197 || (when.size() == 8 ? when[5] != colon : when.size() > 5)) {
198 return result;
199 }
200 const int hour = when.first(n: 2).toInt(ok: &ok);
201 if (!ok)
202 return result;
203 const int minute = when.sliced(pos: 3, n: 2).toInt(ok: &ok);
204 if (!ok)
205 return result;
206 const auto secs = when.size() == 8 ? when.last(n: 2).toInt(ok: &ok) : 0;
207 if (!ok)
208 return result;
209 time = QTime(hour, minute, secs);
210 }
211
212 // Offset: [±hh[mm]]
213 int offset = 0;
214 if (words.size()) {
215 const QStringView zone = words.front();
216 words.erase(pos: words.begin());
217 if (words.size() || !(zone.size() == 3 || zone.size() == 5))
218 return result;
219 bool negate = false;
220 if (zone[0] == u'-')
221 negate = true;
222 else if (zone[0] != u'+')
223 return result;
224 const int hour = zone.sliced(pos: 1, n: 2).toInt(ok: &ok);
225 if (!ok)
226 return result;
227 const auto minute = zone.size() == 5 ? zone.last(n: 2).toInt(ok: &ok) : 0;
228 if (!ok)
229 return result;
230 offset = (hour * 60 + minute) * 60;
231 if (negate)
232 offset = -offset;
233 }
234
235 result.date = date;
236 result.time = time;
237 result.utcOffset = offset;
238 return result;
239}
240#endif // datestring
241
242// Return offset in [+-]HH:mm format
243static QString toOffsetString(Qt::DateFormat format, int offset)
244{
245 return QString::asprintf(format: "%c%02d%s%02d",
246 offset >= 0 ? '+' : '-',
247 qAbs(t: offset) / int(SECS_PER_HOUR),
248 // Qt::ISODate puts : between the hours and minutes, but Qt:TextDate does not:
249 format == Qt::TextDate ? "" : ":",
250 (qAbs(t: offset) / 60) % 60);
251}
252
253#if QT_CONFIG(datestring)
254// Parse offset in [+-]HH[[:]mm] format
255static int fromOffsetString(QStringView offsetString, bool *valid) noexcept
256{
257 *valid = false;
258
259 const int size = offsetString.size();
260 if (size < 2 || size > 6)
261 return 0;
262
263 // sign will be +1 for a positive and -1 for a negative offset
264 int sign;
265
266 // First char must be + or -
267 const QChar signChar = offsetString[0];
268 if (signChar == u'+')
269 sign = 1;
270 else if (signChar == u'-')
271 sign = -1;
272 else
273 return 0;
274
275 // Split the hour and minute parts
276 const QStringView time = offsetString.sliced(pos: 1);
277 qsizetype hhLen = time.indexOf(c: u':');
278 qsizetype mmIndex;
279 if (hhLen == -1)
280 mmIndex = hhLen = 2; // [+-]HHmm or [+-]HH format
281 else
282 mmIndex = hhLen + 1;
283
284 const QStringView hhRef = time.first(n: qMin(a: hhLen, b: time.size()));
285 bool ok = false;
286 const int hour = hhRef.toInt(ok: &ok);
287 if (!ok || hour > 23) // More generous than QTimeZone::MaxUtcOffsetSecs
288 return 0;
289
290 const QStringView mmRef = time.sliced(pos: qMin(a: mmIndex, b: time.size()));
291 const int minute = mmRef.isEmpty() ? 0 : mmRef.toInt(ok: &ok);
292 if (!ok || minute < 0 || minute > 59)
293 return 0;
294
295 *valid = true;
296 return sign * ((hour * 60) + minute) * 60;
297}
298#endif // datestring

304/*!
305 \class QDate
306 \inmodule QtCore
307 \reentrant
308 \brief The QDate class provides date functions.
309
310 A QDate object represents a particular day, regardless of calendar, locale
311 or other settings used when creating it or supplied by the system. It can
312 report the year, month and day of the month that represent the day with
313 respect to the proleptic Gregorian calendar or any calendar supplied as a
314 QCalendar object. QDate objects should be passed by value rather than by
315 reference to const; they simply package \c qint64.
316
317 A QDate object is typically created by giving the year, month, and day
318 numbers explicitly. Note that QDate interprets year numbers less than 100 as
319 presented, i.e., as years 1 through 99, without adding any offset. The
320 static function currentDate() creates a QDate object containing the date
321 read from the system clock. An explicit date can also be set using
322 setDate(). The fromString() function returns a QDate given a string and a
323 date format which is used to interpret the date within the string.
324
325 The year(), month(), and day() functions provide access to the year, month,
326 and day numbers. When more than one of these values is needed, it is more
327 efficient to call QCalendar::partsFromDate(), to save repeating (potentially
328 expensive) calendrical calculations.
329
330 Also, dayOfWeek() and dayOfYear() functions are provided. The same
331 information is provided in textual format by toString(). QLocale can map the
332 day numbers to names, QCalendar can map month numbers to names.
333
334 QDate provides a full set of operators to compare two QDate
335 objects where smaller means earlier, and larger means later.
336
337 You can increment (or decrement) a date by a given number of days
338 using addDays(). Similarly you can use addMonths() and addYears().
339 The daysTo() function returns the number of days between two
340 dates.
341
342 The daysInMonth() and daysInYear() functions return how many days there are
343 in this date's month and year, respectively. The isLeapYear() function
344 indicates whether a date is in a leap year. QCalendar can also supply this
345 information, in some cases more conveniently.
346
347 \section1 Remarks
348
349 \note All conversion to and from string formats is done using the C locale.
350 For localized conversions, see QLocale.
351
352 In the Gregorian calendar, there is no year 0. Dates in that year are
353 considered invalid. The year -1 is the year "1 before Christ" or "1 before
354 common era." The day before 1 January 1 CE, QDate(1, 1, 1), is 31 December
355 1 BCE, QDate(-1, 12, 31). Various other calendars behave similarly; see
356 QCalendar::hasYearZero().
357
358 \section2 Range of Valid Dates
359
360 Dates are stored internally as a Julian Day number, an integer count of
361 every day in a contiguous range, with 24 November 4714 BCE in the Gregorian
362 calendar being Julian Day 0 (1 January 4713 BCE in the Julian calendar).
363 As well as being an efficient and accurate way of storing an absolute date,
364 it is suitable for converting a date into other calendar systems such as
365 Hebrew, Islamic or Chinese. The Julian Day number can be obtained using
366 QDate::toJulianDay() and can be set using QDate::fromJulianDay().
367
368 The range of Julian Day numbers that QDate can represent is, for technical
369 reasons, limited to between -784350574879 and 784354017364, which means from
370 before 2 billion BCE to after 2 billion CE. This is more than seven times as
371 wide as the range of dates a QDateTime can represent.
372
373 \sa QTime, QDateTime, QCalendar, QDateTime::YearRange, QDateEdit, QDateTimeEdit, QCalendarWidget
374*/
375

384/*!
385 Constructs a date with year \a y, month \a m and day \a d.
386
387 The date is understood in terms of the Gregorian calendar. If the specified
388 date is invalid, the date is not set and isValid() returns \c false.
389
390 \warning Years 1 to 99 are interpreted as is. Year 0 is invalid.
391
392 \sa isValid(), QCalendar::dateFromParts()
393*/
394
395QDate::QDate(int y, int m, int d)
396{
397 if (!QGregorianCalendar::julianFromParts(year: y, month: m, day: d, jd: &jd))
398 jd = nullJd();
399}
400
401QDate::QDate(int y, int m, int d, QCalendar cal)
402{
403 *this = cal.dateFromParts(year: y, month: m, day: d);
404}

406/*!
407 \fn QDate::QDate(std::chrono::year_month_day ymd)
408 \fn QDate::QDate(std::chrono::year_month_day_last ymd)
409 \fn QDate::QDate(std::chrono::year_month_weekday ymd)
410 \fn QDate::QDate(std::chrono::year_month_weekday_last ymd)
411
412 \since 6.4
413
414 Constructs a QDate representing the same date as \a ymd. This allows for
415 easy interoperability between the Standard Library calendaring classes and
416 Qt datetime classes.
417
418 For example:
419
420 \snippet code/src_corelib_time_qdatetime.cpp 22
421
422 \note Unlike QDate, std::chrono::year and the related classes feature the
423 year zero. This means that if \a ymd is in the year zero or before, the
424 resulting QDate object will have an year one less than the one specified by
425 \a ymd.
426
427 \note This function requires C++20.
428*/

435 \a days is negative, the returned date will be before the epoch.
436
437 \note This function requires C++20.
438
439 \sa toStdSysDays()

447 is before the epoch, the number of days will be negative.

473/*!
474 Returns the year of this date.
475
476 Uses \a cal as calendar, if supplied, else the Gregorian calendar.
477
478 Returns 0 if the date is invalid. For some calendars, dates before their
479 first year may all be invalid.
480
481 If using a calendar which has a year 0, check using isValid() if the return
482 is 0. Such calendars use negative year numbers in the obvious way, with
483 year 1 preceded by year 0, in turn preceded by year -1 and so on.
484
485 Some calendars, despite having no year 0, have a conventional numbering of
486 the years before their first year, counting backwards from 1. For example,
487 in the proleptic Gregorian calendar, successive years before 1 CE (the first
488 year) are identified as 1 BCE, 2 BCE, 3 BCE and so on. For such calendars,
489 negative year numbers are used to indicate these years before year 1, with
490 -1 indicating the year before 1.
491
492 \sa month(), day(), QCalendar::hasYearZero(), QCalendar::isProleptic(), QCalendar::partsFromDate()
493*/
494
495int QDate::year(QCalendar cal) const
496{
497 if (isValid()) {
498 const auto parts = cal.partsFromDate(date: *this);
499 if (parts.isValid())
500 return parts.year;
501 }
502 return 0;
503}

631/*!
632 Returns the day of the year (1 for the first day) for this date.
633
634 Uses \a cal as calendar if supplied, else the Gregorian calendar.
635 Returns 0 if either the date or the first day of its year is invalid.
636
637 \sa day(), dayOfWeek(), QCalendar::daysInYear()
638*/
639
640int QDate::dayOfYear(QCalendar cal) const
641{
642 if (isValid()) {
643 QDate firstDay = cal.dateFromParts(year: year(cal), month: 1, day: 1);
644 if (firstDay.isValid())
645 return firstDay.daysTo(d: *this) + 1;
646 }
647 return 0;
648}

650/*!
651 \overload
652 */
653
654int QDate::dayOfYear() const
655{
656 if (isValid()) {
657 qint64 first;
658 if (QGregorianCalendar::julianFromParts(year: year(), month: 1, day: 1, jd: &first))
659 return jd - first + 1;
660 }
661 return 0;
662}

724/*!
725 Returns the ISO 8601 week number (1 to 53).
726
727 Returns 0 if the date is invalid. Otherwise, returns the week number for the
728 date. If \a yearNumber is not \nullptr (its default), stores the year as
729 *\a{yearNumber}.
730
731 In accordance with ISO 8601, each week falls in the year to which most of
732 its days belong, in the Gregorian calendar. As ISO 8601's week starts on
733 Monday, this is the year in which the week's Thursday falls. Most years have
734 52 weeks, but some have 53.
735
736 \note *\a{yearNumber} is not always the same as year(). For example, 1
737 January 2000 has week number 52 in the year 1999, and 31 December
738 2002 has week number 1 in the year 2003.
739
740 \sa isValid()
741*/
742
743int QDate::weekNumber(int *yearNumber) const
744{
745 if (!isValid())
746 return 0;
747
748 // This could be replaced by use of QIso8601Calendar, once we implement it.
749 // The Thursday of the same week determines our answer:
750 const QDate thursday(addDays(days: 4 - dayOfWeek()));
751 if (yearNumber)
752 *yearNumber = thursday.year();
753
754 // Week n's Thurs's DOY has 1 <= DOY - 7*(n-1) < 8, so 0 <= DOY + 6 - 7*n < 7:
755 return (thursday.dayOfYear() + 6) / 7;
756}

758#if QT_DEPRECATED_SINCE(6, 9)
759// Only called by deprecated methods (so bootstrap builds warn unused without this #if).
760static QTimeZone asTimeZone(Qt::TimeSpec spec, int offset, const char *warner)
761{
762 if (warner) {
763 switch (spec) {
764 case Qt::TimeZone:
765 qWarning("%s: Pass a QTimeZone instead of Qt::TimeZone.", warner);
766 break;
767 case Qt::LocalTime:
768 if (offset) {
769 qWarning("%s: Ignoring offset (%d seconds) passed with Qt::LocalTime",
770 warner, offset);
771 }
772 break;
773 case Qt::UTC:
774 if (offset) {
775 qWarning("%s: Ignoring offset (%d seconds) passed with Qt::UTC",
776 warner, offset);
777 offset = 0;
778 }
779 break;
780 case Qt::OffsetFromUTC:
781 break;
782 }
783 }
784 return QTimeZone::isUtcOrFixedOffset(spec)
785 ? QTimeZone::fromSecondsAheadOfUtc(offset)
786 : QTimeZone(QTimeZone::LocalTime);
787}

790static bool inDateTimeRange(qint64 jd, bool start)
791{
792 using Bounds = std::numeric_limits<qint64>;
793 if (jd < Bounds::min() + JULIAN_DAY_FOR_EPOCH)
794 return false;
795 jd -= JULIAN_DAY_FOR_EPOCH;
796 const qint64 maxDay = Bounds::max() / MSECS_PER_DAY;
797 const qint64 minDay = Bounds::min() / MSECS_PER_DAY - 1;
798 // (Divisions rounded towards zero, as MSECS_PER_DAY has factors other than two.)
799 // Range includes start of last day and end of first:
800 if (start)
801 return jd > minDay && jd <= maxDay;
802 return jd >= minDay && jd < maxDay;
803}
804
805static QDateTime toEarliest(QDate day, const QTimeZone &zone)
806{
807 Q_ASSERT(!zone.isUtcOrFixedOffset());
808 const auto moment = [=](QTime time) { return QDateTime(day, time, zone); };
809 // Longest routine time-zone transition is 2 hours:
810 QDateTime when = moment(QTime(2, 0));
811 if (!when.isValid()) {
812 // Noon should be safe ...
813 when = moment(QTime(12, 0));
814 if (!when.isValid()) {
815 // ... unless it's a 24-hour jump (moving the date-line)
816 when = moment(QTime(23, 59, 59, 999));
817 if (!when.isValid())
818 return QDateTime();
819 }
820 }
821 int high = when.time().msecsSinceStartOfDay() / 60000;
822 int low = 0;
823 // Binary chop to the right minute
824 while (high > low + 1) {
825 int mid = (high + low) / 2;
826 QDateTime probe = moment(QTime(mid / 60, mid % 60));
827 if (probe.isValid() && probe.date() == day) {
828 high = mid;
829 when = probe;
830 } else {
831 low = mid;
832 }
833 }
834 return when.isValid() ? when : QDateTime();
835}
836
837/*!
838 \since 5.14
839
840 Returns the start-moment of the day.
841
842 When a day starts depends on a how time is described: each day starts and
843 ends earlier for those in time-zones further west and later for those in
844 time-zones further east. The time representation to use can be specified by
845 an optional time \a zone. The default time representation is the system's
846 local time.
847
848 Usually, the start of the day is midnight, 00:00: however, if a time-zone
849 transition causes the given date to skip over that midnight (e.g. a DST
850 spring-forward skipping over the first hour of the day day), the actual
851 earliest time in the day is returned. This can only arise when the time
852 representation is a time-zone or local time.
853
854 When \a zone has a timeSpec() of is Qt::OffsetFromUTC or Qt::UTC, the time
855 representation has no transitions so the start of the day is QTime(0, 0).
856
857 In the rare case of a date that was entirely skipped (this happens when a
858 zone east of the international date-line switches to being west of it), the
859 return shall be invalid. Passing an invalid time-zone as \a zone will also
860 produce an invalid result, as shall dates that start outside the range
861 representable by QDateTime.
862
863 \sa endOfDay()
864*/
865QDateTime QDate::startOfDay(const QTimeZone &zone) const
866{
867 if (!inDateTimeRange(jd, start: true) || !zone.isValid())
868 return QDateTime();
869
870 QDateTime when(*this, QTime(0, 0), zone);
871 if (when.isValid())
872 return when;
873
874#if QT_CONFIG(timezone)
875 // The start of the day must have fallen in a spring-forward's gap; find the spring-forward:
876 if (zone.timeSpec() == Qt::TimeZone && zone.hasTransitions()) {
877 QTimeZone::OffsetData tran
878 // There's unlikely to be another transition before noon tomorrow.
879 // However, the whole of today may have been skipped !
880 = zone.previousTransition(QDateTime(addDays(1), QTime(12, 0), zone));
881 const QDateTime &at = tran.atUtc.toTimeZone(zone);
882 if (at.isValid() && at.date() == *this)
883 return at;
884 }
885#endif
886
887 return toEarliest(day: *this, zone);
888}

936static QDateTime toLatest(QDate day, const QTimeZone &zone)
937{
938 Q_ASSERT(!zone.isUtcOrFixedOffset());
939 const auto moment = [=](QTime time) { return QDateTime(day, time, zone); };
940 // Longest routine time-zone transition is 2 hours:
941 QDateTime when = moment(QTime(21, 59, 59, 999));
942 if (!when.isValid()) {
943 // Noon should be safe ...
944 when = moment(QTime(12, 0));
945 if (!when.isValid()) {
946 // ... unless it's a 24-hour jump (moving the date-line)
947 when = moment(QTime(0, 0));
948 if (!when.isValid())
949 return QDateTime();
950 }
951 }
952 int high = 24 * 60;
953 int low = when.time().msecsSinceStartOfDay() / 60000;
954 // Binary chop to the right minute
955 while (high > low + 1) {
956 int mid = (high + low) / 2;
957 QDateTime probe = moment(QTime(mid / 60, mid % 60, 59, 999));
958 if (probe.isValid() && probe.date() == day) {
959 low = mid;
960 when = probe;
961 } else {
962 high = mid;
963 }
964 }
965 return when.isValid() ? when : QDateTime();
966}

968/*!
969 \since 5.14
970
971 Returns the end-moment of the day.
972
973 When a day ends depends on a how time is described: each day starts and ends
974 earlier for those in time-zones further west and later for those in
975 time-zones further east. The time representation to use can be specified by
976 an optional time \a zone. The default time representation is the system's
977 local time.
978
979 Usually, the end of the day is one millisecond before the midnight, 24:00:
980 however, if a time-zone transition causes the given date to skip over that
981 moment (e.g. a DST spring-forward skipping over 23:00 and the following
982 hour), the actual latest time in the day is returned. This can only arise
983 when the time representation is a time-zone or local time.
984
985 When \a zone has a timeSpec() of Qt::OffsetFromUTC or Qt::UTC, the time
986 representation has no transitions so the end of the day is QTime(23, 59, 59,
987 999).
988
989 In the rare case of a date that was entirely skipped (this happens when a
990 zone east of the international date-line switches to being west of it), the
991 return shall be invalid. Passing an invalid time-zone as \a zone will also
992 produce an invalid result, as shall dates that end outside the range
993 representable by QDateTime.
994
995 \sa startOfDay()
996*/
997QDateTime QDate::endOfDay(const QTimeZone &zone) const
998{
999 if (!inDateTimeRange(jd, start: false) || !zone.isValid())
1000 return QDateTime();
1001
1002 QDateTime when(*this, QTime(23, 59, 59, 999), zone);
1003 if (when.isValid())
1004 return when;
1005
1006#if QT_CONFIG(timezone)
1007 // The end of the day must have fallen in a spring-forward's gap; find the spring-forward:
1008 if (zone.timeSpec() == Qt::TimeZone && zone.hasTransitions()) {
1009 QTimeZone::OffsetData tran
1010 // It's unlikely there's been another transition since yesterday noon.
1011 // However, the whole of today may have been skipped !
1012 = zone.nextTransition(QDateTime(addDays(-1), QTime(12, 0), zone));
1013 const QDateTime &at = tran.atUtc.toTimeZone(zone);
1014 if (at.isValid() && at.date() == *this)
1015 return at;
1016 }
1017#endif
1018
1019 return toLatest(day: *this, zone);
1020}

1094/*!

1098 of the string.
1099
1100 If the \a format is Qt::TextDate, the string is formatted in the default
1101 way. The day and month names will be in English. An example of this
1102 formatting is "Sat May 20 1995". For localized formatting, see
1103 \l{QLocale::toString()}.
1104
1105 If the \a format is Qt::ISODate, the string format corresponds
1106 to the ISO 8601 extended specification for representations of
1107 dates and times, taking the form yyyy-MM-dd, where yyyy is the
1108 year, MM is the month of the year (between 01 and 12), and dd is
1109 the day of the month between 01 and 31.

1112 an \l{RFC 2822} compatible way. An example of this formatting is
1113 "20 May 1995".

1116
1117 \warning The Qt::ISODate format is only valid for years in the
1118 range 0 to 9999.
1119

1121*/
1122QString QDate::toString(Qt::DateFormat format) const
1123{
1124 if (!isValid())
1125 return QString();
1126
1127 switch (format) {
1128 case Qt::RFC2822Date:
1129 return QLocale::c().toString(date: *this, format: u"dd MMM yyyy");
1130 default:
1131 case Qt::TextDate:

1133 case Qt::ISODate:

1140/*!
1141 \fn QString QDate::toString(const QString &format, QCalendar cal) const
1142 \fn QString QDate::toString(QStringView format, QCalendar cal) const
1143
1144 Returns the date as a string. The \a format parameter determines the format
1145 of the result string. If \a cal is supplied, it determines the calendar used
1146 to represent the date; it defaults to Gregorian.
1147
1148 These expressions may be used:
1149
1150 \table
1151 \header \li Expression \li Output
1152 \row \li d \li The day as a number without a leading zero (1 to 31)
1153 \row \li dd \li The day as a number with a leading zero (01 to 31)
1154 \row \li ddd \li The abbreviated day name ('Mon' to 'Sun').
1155 \row \li dddd \li The long day name ('Monday' to 'Sunday').
1156 \row \li M \li The month as a number without a leading zero (1 to 12)
1157 \row \li MM \li The month as a number with a leading zero (01 to 12)
1158 \row \li MMM \li The abbreviated month name ('Jan' to 'Dec').
1159 \row \li MMMM \li The long month name ('January' to 'December').
1160 \row \li yy \li The year as a two digit number (00 to 99)
1161 \row \li yyyy \li The year as a four digit number. If the year is negative,
1162 a minus sign is prepended, making five characters.
1163 \endtable
1164
1165 Any sequence of characters enclosed in single quotes will be included
1166 verbatim in the output string (stripped of the quotes), even if it contains
1167 formatting characters. Two consecutive single quotes ("''") are replaced by
1168 a single quote in the output. All other characters in the format string are
1169 included verbatim in the output string.
1170
1171 Formats without separators (e.g. "ddMM") are supported but must be used with
1172 care, as the resulting strings aren't always reliably readable (e.g. if "dM"
1173 produces "212" it could mean either the 2nd of December or the 21st of
1174 February).
1175
1176 Example format strings (assuming that the QDate is the 20 July
1177 1969):
1178
1179 \table
1180 \header \li Format \li Result
1181 \row \li dd.MM.yyyy \li 20.07.1969
1182 \row \li ddd MMMM d yy \li Sun July 20 69
1183 \row \li 'The day is' dddd \li The day is Sunday
1184 \endtable
1185
1186 If the datetime is invalid, an empty string will be returned.
1187
1188 \note Day and month names are given in English (C locale). To get localized
1189 month and day names, use QLocale::system().toString().
1190
1191 \note If a format character is repeated more times than the longest
1192 expression in the table above using it, this part of the format will be read
1193 as several expressions with no separator between them; the longest above,
1194 possibly repeated as many times as there are copies of it, ending with a
1195 residue that may be a shorter expression. Thus \c{'MMMMMMMMMM'} for a date
1196 in May will contribute \c{"MayMay05"} to the output.
1197
1198 \sa fromString(), QDateTime::toString(), QTime::toString(), QLocale::toString()
1199
1200*/
1201QString QDate::toString(QStringView format, QCalendar cal) const
1202{
1203 return QLocale::c().toString(date: *this, format, cal);
1204}

1291/*!
1292 \fn QDate QDate::addDuration(std::chrono::days ndays) const
1293
1294 \since 6.4
1295
1296 Returns a QDate object containing a date \a ndays later than the
1297 date of this object (or earlier if \a ndays is negative).
1298
1299 Returns a null date if the current date is invalid or the new date is
1300 out of range.
1301
1302 \note Adding durations expressed in \c{std::chrono::months} or
1303 \c{std::chrono::years} does not yield the same result obtained by using
1304 addMonths() or addYears(). The former are fixed durations, calculated in
1305 relation to the solar year; the latter use the Gregorian calendar definitions
1306 of months/years.
1307
1308 \note This function requires C++20.
1309
1310 \sa addMonths(), addYears(), daysTo()
1311*/
1312
1313/*!
1314 Returns a QDate object containing a date \a nmonths later than the
1315 date of this object (or earlier if \a nmonths is negative).
1316
1317 Uses \a cal as calendar, if supplied, else the Gregorian calendar.
1318
1319 \note If the ending day/month combination does not exist in the resulting
1320 month/year, this function will return a date that is the latest valid date
1321 in the selected month.
1322
1323 \sa addDays(), addYears()
1324*/
1325
1326QDate QDate::addMonths(int nmonths, QCalendar cal) const
1327{
1328 if (!isValid())
1329 return QDate();
1330
1331 if (nmonths == 0)
1332 return *this;
1333
1334 auto parts = cal.partsFromDate(date: *this);
1335
1336 if (!parts.isValid())
1337 return QDate();
1338 Q_ASSERT(parts.year || cal.hasYearZero());
1339
1340 parts.month += nmonths;
1341 while (parts.month <= 0) {
1342 if (--parts.year || cal.hasYearZero())
1343 parts.month += cal.monthsInYear(year: parts.year);
1344 }
1345 int count = cal.monthsInYear(year: parts.year);
1346 while (parts.month > count) {
1347 parts.month -= count;
1348 count = (++parts.year || cal.hasYearZero()) ? cal.monthsInYear(year: parts.year) : 0;
1349 }
1350
1351 return fixedDate(parts, cal);
1352}
1353
1354/*!
1355 \overload
1356*/
1357
1358QDate QDate::addMonths(int nmonths) const
1359{
1360 if (isNull())
1361 return QDate();
1362
1363 if (nmonths == 0)
1364 return *this;
1365
1366 auto parts = QGregorianCalendar::partsFromJulian(jd);
1367
1368 if (!parts.isValid())
1369 return QDate();
1370 Q_ASSERT(parts.year);
1371
1372 parts.month += nmonths;
1373 while (parts.month <= 0) {
1374 if (--parts.year) // skip over year 0
1375 parts.month += 12;
1376 }
1377 while (parts.month > 12) {
1378 parts.month -= 12;
1379 if (!++parts.year) // skip over year 0
1380 ++parts.year;
1381 }
1382
1383 return fixedDate(parts);
1384}

1387 Returns a QDate object containing a date \a nyears later than the
1388 date of this object (or earlier if \a nyears is negative).

1391
1392 \note If the ending day/month combination does not exist in the resulting
1393 year (e.g., for the Gregorian calendar, if the date was Feb 29 and the final
1394 year is not a leap year), this function will return a date that is the
1395 latest valid date in the given month (in the example, Feb 28).
1396
1397 \sa addDays(), addMonths()
1398*/
1399
1400QDate QDate::addYears(int nyears, QCalendar cal) const
1401{
1402 if (!isValid())
1403 return QDate();
1404
1405 auto parts = cal.partsFromDate(date: *this);
1406 if (!parts.isValid())
1407 return QDate();
1408
1409 int old_y = parts.year;
1410 parts.year += nyears;
1411
1412 // If we just crossed (or hit) a missing year zero, adjust year by +/- 1:
1413 if (!cal.hasYearZero() && ((old_y > 0) != (parts.year > 0) || !parts.year))
1414 parts.year += nyears > 0 ? +1 : -1;
1415
1416 return fixedDate(parts, cal);
1417}
1418
1419/*!
1420 \overload
1421*/
1422
1423QDate QDate::addYears(int nyears) const
1424{
1425 if (isNull())
1426 return QDate();
1427
1428 auto parts = QGregorianCalendar::partsFromJulian(jd);
1429 if (!parts.isValid())
1430 return QDate();
1431
1432 int old_y = parts.year;
1433 parts.year += nyears;
1434
1435 // If we just crossed (or hit) a missing year zero, adjust year by +/- 1:
1436 if ((old_y > 0) != (parts.year > 0) || !parts.year)
1437 parts.year += nyears > 0 ? +1 : -1;
1438
1439 return fixedDate(parts);
1440}

1513#if QT_CONFIG(datestring) // depends on, so implies, textdate
1514namespace {
1515
1516struct ParsedInt { qulonglong value = 0; bool ok = false; };
1517
1518/*
1519 /internal
1520
1521 Read a whole number that must be the whole text. QStringView::toULongLong()
1522 will happily ignore spaces and accept signs; but various date formats'
1523 fields (e.g. all in ISO) should not.
1524*/
1525ParsedInt readInt(QStringView text)
1526{
1527 ParsedInt result;
1528 for (QStringIterator it(text); it.hasNext();) {
1529 if (!QChar::isDigit(ucs4: it.next()))
1530 return result;
1531 }
1532 result.value = text.toULongLong(ok: &result.ok);
1533 return result;
1534}
1535
1536}

1538/*!
1539 \fn QDate QDate::fromString(const QString &string, Qt::DateFormat format)
1540
1541 Returns the QDate represented by the \a string, using the
1542 \a format given, or an invalid date if the string cannot be
1543 parsed.
1544
1545 Note for Qt::TextDate: only English month names (e.g. "Jan" in short form or
1546 "January" in long form) are recognized.
1547
1548 \sa toString(), QLocale::toDate()
1549*/
1550
1551/*!
1552 \overload
1553 \since 6.0
1554*/
1555QDate QDate::fromString(QStringView string, Qt::DateFormat format)
1556{
1557 if (string.isEmpty())
1558 return QDate();
1559
1560 switch (format) {
1561 case Qt::RFC2822Date:
1562 return rfcDateImpl(s: string).date;
1563 default:
1564 case Qt::TextDate: {
1565 // Documented as "ddd MMM d yyyy"
1566 QVarLengthArray<QStringView, 4> parts;
1567 auto tokens = string.tokenize(needle: u' ', flags: Qt::SkipEmptyParts);
1568 auto it = tokens.begin();
1569 for (int i = 0; i < 4 && it != tokens.end(); ++i, ++it)
1570 parts.emplace_back(args: *it);
1571
1572 if (parts.size() != 4 || it != tokens.end())
1573 return QDate();
1574
1575 bool ok = false;
1576 int year = parts.at(idx: 3).toInt(ok: &ok);
1577 int day = ok ? parts.at(idx: 2).toInt(ok: &ok) : 0;
1578 if (!ok || !day)
1579 return QDate();
1580
1581 const int month = fromShortMonthName(monthName: parts.at(idx: 1));
1582 if (month == -1) // Month name matches no English or localised name.
1583 return QDate();
1584
1585 return QDate(year, month, day);
1586 }
1587 case Qt::ISODate:
1588 // Semi-strict parsing, must be long enough and have punctuators as separators
1589 if (string.size() >= 10 && string[4].isPunct() && string[7].isPunct()
1590 && (string.size() == 10 || !string[10].isDigit())) {
1591 const ParsedInt year = readInt(text: string.first(n: 4));
1592 const ParsedInt month = readInt(text: string.sliced(pos: 5, n: 2));
1593 const ParsedInt day = readInt(text: string.sliced(pos: 8, n: 2));
1594 if (year.ok && year.value > 0 && year.value <= 9999 && month.ok && day.ok)
1595 return QDate(year.value, month.value, day.value);
1596 }
1597 break;
1598 }
1599 return QDate();
1600}

1750/*!
1751 \class QTime
1752 \inmodule QtCore
1753 \reentrant
1754
1755 \brief The QTime class provides clock time functions.
1756
1757 A QTime object contains a clock time, which it can express as the numbers of
1758 hours, minutes, seconds, and milliseconds since midnight. It provides
1759 functions for comparing times and for manipulating a time by adding a number
1760 of milliseconds. QTime objects should be passed by value rather than by
1761 reference to const; they simply package \c int.
1762
1763 QTime uses the 24-hour clock format; it has no concept of AM/PM.
1764 Unlike QDateTime, QTime knows nothing about time zones or
1765 daylight-saving time (DST).
1766
1767 A QTime object is typically created either by giving the number of hours,
1768 minutes, seconds, and milliseconds explicitly, or by using the static
1769 function currentTime(), which creates a QTime object that represents the
1770 system's local time.
1771
1772 The hour(), minute(), second(), and msec() functions provide
1773 access to the number of hours, minutes, seconds, and milliseconds
1774 of the time. The same information is provided in textual format by
1775 the toString() function.
1776
1777 The addSecs() and addMSecs() functions provide the time a given
1778 number of seconds or milliseconds later than a given time.
1779 Correspondingly, the number of seconds or milliseconds
1780 between two times can be found using secsTo() or msecsTo().
1781
1782 QTime provides a full set of operators to compare two QTime
1783 objects; an earlier time is considered smaller than a later one;
1784 if A.msecsTo(B) is positive, then A < B.
1785
1786 QTime objects can also be created from a text representation using
1787 fromString() and converted to a string representation using toString(). All
1788 conversion to and from string formats is done using the C locale. For
1789 localized conversions, see QLocale.
1790
1791 \sa QDate, QDateTime
1792*/
1793

1948/*!
1949 \fn QString QTime::toString(const QString &format) const
1950 \fn QString QTime::toString(QStringView format) const
1951
1952 Returns the time as a string. The \a format parameter determines
1953 the format of the result string.
1954
1955 These expressions may be used:
1956
1957 \table
1958 \header \li Expression \li Output
1959 \row \li h
1960 \li The hour without a leading zero (0 to 23 or 1 to 12 if AM/PM display)
1961 \row \li hh
1962 \li The hour with a leading zero (00 to 23 or 01 to 12 if AM/PM display)
1963 \row \li H
1964 \li The hour without a leading zero (0 to 23, even with AM/PM display)
1965 \row \li HH
1966 \li The hour with a leading zero (00 to 23, even with AM/PM display)
1967 \row \li m \li The minute without a leading zero (0 to 59)
1968 \row \li mm \li The minute with a leading zero (00 to 59)
1969 \row \li s \li The whole second, without any leading zero (0 to 59)
1970 \row \li ss \li The whole second, with a leading zero where applicable (00 to 59)
1971 \row \li z or zz

1973 without trailing zeroes. Thus \c{"s.z"} reports the seconds to full
1974 available (millisecond) precision without trailing zeroes (0 to
1975 999). For example, \c{"s.z"} would produce \c{"0.25"} for a time a
1976 quarter second into a minute.
1977 \row \li zzz
1978 \li The fractional part of the second, to millisecond precision,
1979 including trailing zeroes where applicable (000 to 999). For
1980 example, \c{"ss.zzz"} would produce \c{"00.250"} for a time a
1981 quarter second into a minute.
1982 \row \li AP or A
1983 \li Use AM/PM display. \c A/AP will be replaced by 'AM' or 'PM'. In
1984 localized forms (only relevant to \l{QLocale::toString()}), the
1985 locale-appropriate text is converted to upper-case.
1986 \row \li ap or a
1987 \li Use am/pm display. \c a/ap will be replaced by 'am' or 'pm'. In
1988 localized forms (only relevant to \l{QLocale::toString()}), the
1989 locale-appropriate text is converted to lower-case.
1990 \row \li aP or Ap
1991 \li Use AM/PM display (since 6.3). \c aP/Ap will be replaced by 'AM' or
1992 'PM'. In localized forms (only relevant to
1993 \l{QLocale::toString()}), the locale-appropriate text (returned by
1994 \l{QLocale::amText()} or \l{QLocale::pmText()}) is used without
1995 change of case.
1996 \row \li t
1997 \li The timezone abbreviation (for example "CEST"). Note that time zone
1998 abbreviations are not unique. In particular, \l toString() cannot
1999 parse this.
2000 \row \li tt
2001 \li The timezone's offset from UTC with no colon between the hours and
2002 minutes (for example "+0200").
2003 \row \li ttt
2004 \li The timezone's offset from UTC with a colon between the hours and
2005 minutes (for example "+02:00").
2006 \row \li tttt
2007 \li The timezone name (for example "Europe/Berlin"). Note that this
2008 gives no indication of whether the datetime was in daylight-saving
2009 time or standard time, which may lead to ambiguity if the datetime
2010 falls in an hour repeated by a transition between the two. The name
2011 used is the one provided by \l QTimeZone::displayName() with the \l
2012 QTimeZone::LongName type. This may depend on the operating system
2013 in use.
2014 \endtable
2015
2016 Any non-empty sequence of characters enclosed in single quotes will be
2017 included verbatim in the output string (stripped of the quotes), even if it
2018 contains formatting characters. Two consecutive single quotes ("''") are
2019 replaced by a single quote in the output. All other characters in the format
2020 string are included verbatim in the output string.

2032 \row \li h:m:s ap \li 2:13:9 pm
2033 \row \li H:m:s a \li 14:13:9 pm

2041 \note If a format character is repeated more times than the longest

2059 milliseconds \a ms.
2060
2061 \a h must be in the range 0 to 23, \a m and \a s must be in the

2071 mds = NullTime; // make this invalid

2102 If \a t is earlier than this time, the number of seconds returned
2103 is negative.
2104
2105 Because QTime measures time within a day and there are 86400
2106 seconds in a day, the result is always between -86400 and 86400.
2107
2108 secsTo() does not take into account any milliseconds.
2109
2110 Returns 0 if either time is invalid.
2111
2112 \sa addSecs(), QDateTime::secsTo()
2113*/
2114
2115int QTime::secsTo(QTime t) const
2116{
2117 if (!isValid() || !t.isValid())
2118 return 0;
2119
2120 // Truncate milliseconds as we do not want to consider them.
2121 int ourSeconds = ds() / MSECS_PER_SEC;
2122 int theirSeconds = t.ds() / MSECS_PER_SEC;
2123 return theirSeconds - ourSeconds;
2124}

2240#if QT_CONFIG(datestring) // depends on, so implies, textdate
2241
2242static QTime fromIsoTimeString(QStringView string, Qt::DateFormat format, bool *isMidnight24)
2243{
2244 Q_ASSERT(format == Qt::TextDate || format == Qt::ISODate || format == Qt::ISODateWithMs);
2245 if (isMidnight24)
2246 *isMidnight24 = false;
2247 // Match /\d\d(:\d\d(:\d\d)?)?([,.]\d+)?/ as "HH[:mm[:ss]][.zzz]"
2248 // The fractional part, if present, is in the same units as the field it follows.
2249 // TextDate restricts fractional parts to the seconds field.
2250
2251 QStringView tail;
2252 const int dot = string.indexOf(c: u'.'), comma = string.indexOf(c: u',');
2253 if (dot != -1) {
2254 tail = string.sliced(pos: dot + 1);
2255 if (tail.indexOf(c: u'.') != -1) // Forbid second dot:
2256 return QTime();
2257 string = string.first(n: dot);
2258 } else if (comma != -1) {
2259 tail = string.sliced(pos: comma + 1);
2260 string = string.first(n: comma);
2261 }
2262 if (tail.indexOf(c: u',') != -1) // Forbid comma after first dot-or-comma:
2263 return QTime();
2264
2265 const ParsedInt frac = readInt(text: tail);
2266 // There must be *some* digits in a fractional part; and it must be all digits:
2267 if (tail.isEmpty() ? dot != -1 || comma != -1 : !frac.ok)
2268 return QTime();
2269 Q_ASSERT(frac.ok ^ tail.isEmpty());
2270 double fraction = frac.ok ? frac.value * std::pow(x: 0.1, y: tail.size()) : 0.0;
2271
2272 const int size = string.size();
2273 if (size < 2 || size > 8)
2274 return QTime();
2275
2276 ParsedInt hour = readInt(text: string.first(n: 2));
2277 if (!hour.ok || hour.value > (format == Qt::TextDate ? 23 : 24))
2278 return QTime();
2279
2280 ParsedInt minute;
2281 if (string.size() > 2) {
2282 if (string[2] == u':' && string.size() > 4)
2283 minute = readInt(text: string.sliced(pos: 3, n: 2));
2284 if (!minute.ok || minute.value >= MINS_PER_HOUR)
2285 return QTime();
2286 } else if (format == Qt::TextDate) { // Requires minutes
2287 return QTime();
2288 } else if (frac.ok) {
2289 Q_ASSERT(!(fraction < 0.0) && fraction < 1.0);
2290 fraction *= MINS_PER_HOUR;
2291 minute.value = qulonglong(fraction);
2292 fraction -= minute.value;
2293 }
2294
2295 ParsedInt second;
2296 if (string.size() > 5) {
2297 if (string[5] == u':' && string.size() == 8)
2298 second = readInt(text: string.sliced(pos: 6, n: 2));
2299 if (!second.ok || second.value >= SECS_PER_MIN)
2300 return QTime();
2301 } else if (frac.ok) {
2302 if (format == Qt::TextDate) // Doesn't allow fraction of minutes
2303 return QTime();
2304 Q_ASSERT(!(fraction < 0.0) && fraction < 1.0);
2305 fraction *= SECS_PER_MIN;
2306 second.value = qulonglong(fraction);
2307 fraction -= second.value;
2308 }
2309
2310 Q_ASSERT(!(fraction < 0.0) && fraction < 1.0);
2311 // Round millis to nearest (unlike minutes and seconds, rounded down):
2312 int msec = frac.ok ? qRound(d: MSECS_PER_SEC * fraction) : 0;
2313 // But handle overflow gracefully:
2314 if (msec == MSECS_PER_SEC) {
2315 // If we can (when data were otherwise valid) validly propagate overflow
2316 // into other fields, do so:
2317 if (isMidnight24 || hour.value < 23 || minute.value < 59 || second.value < 59) {
2318 msec = 0;
2319 if (++second.value == SECS_PER_MIN) {
2320 second.value = 0;
2321 if (++minute.value == MINS_PER_HOUR) {
2322 minute.value = 0;
2323 ++hour.value;
2324 // May need to propagate further via isMidnight24, see below
2325 }
2326 }
2327 } else {
2328 // QTime::fromString() or Qt::TextDate: rounding up would cause
2329 // 23:59:59.999... to become invalid; clip to 999 ms instead:
2330 msec = MSECS_PER_SEC - 1;
2331 }
2332 }
2333
2334 // For ISO date format, 24:0:0 means 0:0:0 on the next day:
2335 if (hour.value == 24 && minute.value == 0 && second.value == 0 && msec == 0) {
2336 Q_ASSERT(format != Qt::TextDate); // It clipped hour at 23, above.
2337 if (isMidnight24)
2338 *isMidnight24 = true;
2339 hour.value = 0;
2340 }
2341
2342 return QTime(hour.value, minute.value, second.value, msec);
2343}

2374/*!
2375 \fn QTime QTime::fromString(const QString &string, const QString &format)
2376
2377 Returns the QTime represented by the \a string, using the \a
2378 format given, or an invalid time if the string cannot be parsed.
2379
2380 These expressions may be used for the format:
2381
2382 \table
2383 \header \li Expression \li Output
2384 \row \li h
2385 \li The hour without a leading zero (0 to 23 or 1 to 12 if AM/PM display)
2386 \row \li hh
2387 \li The hour with a leading zero (00 to 23 or 01 to 12 if AM/PM display)
2388 \row \li H
2389 \li The hour without a leading zero (0 to 23, even with AM/PM display)
2390 \row \li HH
2391 \li The hour with a leading zero (00 to 23, even with AM/PM display)
2392 \row \li m \li The minute without a leading zero (0 to 59)
2393 \row \li mm \li The minute with a leading zero (00 to 59)
2394 \row \li s \li The whole second, without any leading zero (0 to 59)
2395 \row \li ss \li The whole second, with a leading zero where applicable (00 to 59)
2396 \row \li z or zz
2397 \li The fractional part of the second, as would usually follow a
2398 decimal point, without requiring trailing zeroes (0 to 999). Thus
2399 \c{"s.z"} matches the seconds with up to three digits of fractional
2400 part supplying millisecond precision, without needing trailing
2401 zeroes. For example, \c{"s.z"} would recognize either \c{"00.250"}
2402 or \c{"0.25"} as representing a time a quarter second into its
2403 minute.
2404 \row \li zzz
2405 \li Three digit fractional part of the second, to millisecond
2406 precision, including trailing zeroes where applicable (000 to 999).
2407 For example, \c{"ss.zzz"} would reject \c{"0.25"} but recognize
2408 \c{"00.250"} as representing a time a quarter second into its
2409 minute.
2410 \row \li AP, A, ap, a, aP or Ap
2411 \li Either 'AM' indicating a time before 12:00 or 'PM' for later times,
2412 matched case-insensitively.
2413 \endtable
2414
2415 All other input characters will be treated as text. Any non-empty sequence
2416 of characters enclosed in single quotes will also be treated (stripped of
2417 the quotes) as text and not be interpreted as expressions.
2418
2419 \snippet code/src_corelib_time_qdatetime.cpp 6
2420
2421 If the format is not satisfied, an invalid QTime is returned.
2422 Expressions that do not expect leading zeroes to be given (h, m, s
2423 and z) are greedy. This means that they will use two digits (or three, for z) even if
2424 this puts them outside the range of accepted values and leaves too
2425 few digits for other sections. For example, the following string
2426 could have meant 00:07:10, but the m will grab two digits, resulting
2427 in an invalid time:
2428
2429 \snippet code/src_corelib_time_qdatetime.cpp 7
2430
2431 Any field that is not represented in the format will be set to zero.
2432 For example:
2433
2434 \snippet code/src_corelib_time_qdatetime.cpp 8
2435
2436 \note If localized forms of am or pm (the AP, ap, Ap, aP, A or a formats)
2437 are to be recognized, use QLocale::system().toTime().
2438
2439 \note If a format character is repeated more times than the longest
2440 expression in the table above using it, this part of the format will be read
2441 as several expressions with no separator between them; the longest above,
2442 possibly repeated as many times as there are copies of it, ending with a
2443 residue that may be a shorter expression. Thus \c{'HHHHH'} would match
2444 \c{"08088"} or \c{"080808"} and set the hour to 8; if the time string
2445 contained "070809" it would "match" but produce an inconsistent result,
2446 leading to an invalid time.
2447
2448 \sa toString(), QDateTime::fromString(), QDate::fromString(),
2449 QLocale::toTime(), QLocale::toDateTime()

2523// True if combining days with millis overflows; otherwise, stores result in *sumMillis
2524// The inputs should not have opposite signs.
2525static inline bool daysAndMillisOverflow(qint64 days, qint64 millisInDay, qint64 *sumMillis)
2526{
2527 return mul_overflow(v1: days, std::integral_constant<qint64, MSECS_PER_DAY>(), r: sumMillis)

2531// Converts a date/time value into msecs
2532static qint64 timeToMSecs(QDate date, QTime time)
2533{
2534 qint64 days = date.toJulianDay() - JULIAN_DAY_FOR_EPOCH;
2535 qint64 msecs, dayms = time.msecsSinceStartOfDay();
2536 if (days < 0 && dayms > 0) {
2537 ++days;
2538 dayms -= MSECS_PER_DAY;
2539 }
2540 if (daysAndMillisOverflow(days, millisInDay: dayms, sumMillis: &msecs)) {
2541 using Bound = std::numeric_limits<qint64>;
2542 return days < 0 ? Bound::min() : Bound::max();
2543 }
2544 return msecs;

2547/*!
2548 \internal
2549 Tests whether system functions can handle a given time.
2550
2551 The range of milliseconds for which the time_t-based functions work depends
2552 somewhat on platform (see computeSystemMillisRange() for details). This
2553 function tests whether the UTC time \a millis milliseconds from the epoch is
2554 in the supported range.
2555
2556 To test a local time, pass an upper bound on the magnitude of time-zone
2557 correction potentially needed as \a slack: in this case the range is
2558 extended by this many milliseconds at each end (where applicable). The
2559 function then returns true precisely if \a millis is within this (possibly)
2560 widened range. This doesn't guarantee that the time_t functions can handle
2561 the time, so check their returns to be sure. Values for which the function
2562 returns false should be assumed unrepresentable.
2563*/
2564static inline bool millisInSystemRange(qint64 millis, qint64 slack = 0)
2565{
2566 static const auto bounds = QLocalTime::computeSystemMillisRange();
2567 return (bounds.minClip || millis >= bounds.min - slack)
2568 && (bounds.maxClip || millis <= bounds.max + slack);
2569}

2571/*!
2572 \internal
2573 Returns a year, in the system range, with the same day-of-week pattern
2574
2575 Returns the number of a year, in the range supported by system time_t
2576 functions, that starts and ends on the same days of the week as \a year.
2577 This implies it is a leap year precisely if \a year is. If year is before
2578 the epoch, a year early in the supported range is used; otherwise, one late
2579 in that range. For a leap year, this may be as much as 26 years years from
2580 the range's relevant end; for normal years at most a decade from the end.
2581
2582 This ensures that any DST rules based on, e.g., the last Sunday in a
2583 particular month will select the same date in the returned year as they
2584 would if applied to \a year. Of course, the zone's rules may be different in
2585 \a year than in the selected year, but it's hard to do better.
2586*/
2587static int systemTimeYearMatching(int year)
2588{
2589#if defined(Q_OS_WIN) || defined(Q_OS_WASM)// They don't support times before the epoch
2590 static constexpr int forLeapEarly[] = { 1984, 1996, 1980, 1992, 1976, 1988, 1972 };
2591 static constexpr int regularEarly[] = { 1978, 1973, 1974, 1975, 1970, 1971, 1977 };
2592#else // First year fully in 32-bit time_t range is 1902
2593 static constexpr int forLeapEarly[] = { 1928, 1912, 1924, 1908, 1920, 1904, 1916 };
2594 static constexpr int regularEarly[] = { 1905, 1906, 1907, 1902, 1903, 1909, 1910 };
2595#endif
2596 static constexpr int forLeapLate[] = { 2012, 2024, 2036, 2020, 2032, 2016, 2028 };
2597 static constexpr int regularLate[] = { 2034, 2035, 2030, 2031, 2037, 2027, 2033 };
2598 const int dow = QGregorianCalendar::yearStartWeekDay(year);
2599 Q_ASSERT(dow == QDate(year, 1, 1).dayOfWeek());
2600 const int res = (QGregorianCalendar::leapTest(year)
2601 ? (year < 1970 ? forLeapEarly : forLeapLate)
2602 : (year < 1970 ? regularEarly : regularLate))[dow == 7 ? 0 : dow];
2603 Q_ASSERT(QDate(res, 1, 1).dayOfWeek() == dow);
2604 Q_ASSERT(QDate(res, 12, 31).dayOfWeek() == QDate(year, 12, 31).dayOfWeek());
2605 return res;
2606}

2608// Sets up d and status to represent local time at the given UTC msecs since epoch:
2609QDateTimePrivate::ZoneState QDateTimePrivate::expressUtcAsLocal(qint64 utcMSecs)
2610{
2611 ZoneState result{utcMSecs};
2612 // Within the time_t supported range, localtime() can handle it:
2613 if (millisInSystemRange(millis: utcMSecs)) {
2614 result = QLocalTime::utcToLocal(utcMillis: utcMSecs);
2615 if (result.valid)
2616 return result;
2617 }
2618
2619 // Docs state any LocalTime after 2038-01-18 *will* have any DST applied.
2620 // When this falls outside the supported range, we need to fake it.
2621#if QT_CONFIG(timezone) // Use the system time-zone.
2622 if (const auto sys = QTimeZone::systemTimeZone(); sys.isValid()) {
2623 result.offset = sys.d->offsetFromUtc(utcMSecs);
2624 if (add_overflow(utcMSecs, result.offset * MSECS_PER_SEC, &result.when))
2625 return result;
2626 result.dst = sys.d->isDaylightTime(utcMSecs) ? DaylightTime : StandardTime;
2627 result.valid = true;
2628 return result;
2629 }
2630#endif // timezone
2631
2632 // Kludge
2633 // Do the conversion in a year with the same days of the week, so DST
2634 // dates might be right, and adjust by the number of days that was off:
2635 const qint64 jd = msecsToJulianDay(msecs: utcMSecs);
2636 const auto ymd = QGregorianCalendar::partsFromJulian(jd);
2637 qint64 fakeJd, diffMillis, fakeUtc;
2638 if (Q_UNLIKELY(!QGregorianCalendar::julianFromParts(systemTimeYearMatching(ymd.year),
2639 ymd.month, ymd.day, &fakeJd)
2640 || mul_overflow(jd - fakeJd, std::integral_constant<qint64, MSECS_PER_DAY>(),
2641 &diffMillis)
2642 || sub_overflow(utcMSecs, diffMillis, &fakeUtc))) {
2643 return result;
2644 }
2645
2646 result = QLocalTime::utcToLocal(utcMillis: fakeUtc);
2647 // Now correct result.when for the use of the fake date:
2648 if (!result.valid || add_overflow(v1: result.when, v2: diffMillis, r: &result.when)) {
2649 // If utcToLocal() failed, its return has the fake when; restore utcMSecs.
2650 // Fail on overflow, but preserve offset and DST-ness.
2651 result.when = utcMSecs;
2652 result.valid = false;
2653 }
2654 return result;
2655}

2657static auto millisToWithinRange(qint64 millis)
2658{
2659 struct R {
2660 qint64 shifted = 0;
2661 bool good = false;
2662 } result;
2663 qint64 jd = msecsToJulianDay(msecs: millis), fakeJd;
2664 auto ymd = QGregorianCalendar::partsFromJulian(jd);
2665 result.good = QGregorianCalendar::julianFromParts(year: systemTimeYearMatching(year: ymd.year),
2666 month: ymd.month, day: ymd.day, jd: &fakeJd)
2667 && !daysAndMillisOverflow(days: fakeJd - jd, millisInDay: millis, sumMillis: &result.shifted);
2668 return result;
2669}

2671QString QDateTimePrivate::localNameAtMillis(qint64 millis, DaylightStatus dst)
2672{
2673 QString abbreviation;
2674 if (millisInSystemRange(millis, slack: MSECS_PER_DAY)) {
2675 abbreviation = QLocalTime::localTimeAbbbreviationAt(local: millis, dst);
2676 if (!abbreviation.isEmpty())
2677 return abbreviation;
2678 }
2679
2680 // Otherwise, outside the system range.
2681#if QT_CONFIG(timezone)
2682 // Use the system zone:
2683 const auto sys = QTimeZone::systemTimeZone();
2684 if (sys.isValid()) {
2685 ZoneState state = zoneStateAtMillis(sys, millis, dst);
2686 if (state.valid)
2687 return sys.d->abbreviation(state.when - state.offset * MSECS_PER_SEC);
2688 }
2689#endif // timezone
2690
2691 // Kludge
2692 // Use a time in the system range with the same day-of-week pattern to its year:
2693 auto fake = millisToWithinRange(millis);
2694 if (Q_LIKELY(fake.good))
2695 return QLocalTime::localTimeAbbbreviationAt(local: fake.shifted, dst);
2696
2697 // Overflow, apparently.
2698 return {};
2699}
2700
2701// Determine the offset from UTC at the given local time as millis.
2702QDateTimePrivate::ZoneState QDateTimePrivate::localStateAtMillis(qint64 millis, DaylightStatus dst)
2703{
2704 // First, if millis is within a day of the viable range, try mktime() in
2705 // case it does fall in the range and gets useful information:
2706 if (millisInSystemRange(millis, slack: MSECS_PER_DAY)) {
2707 auto result = QLocalTime::mapLocalTime(local: millis, dst);
2708 if (result.valid)
2709 return result;
2710 }
2711
2712 // Otherwise, outside the system range.
2713#if QT_CONFIG(timezone)
2714 // Use the system zone:
2715 const auto sys = QTimeZone::systemTimeZone();
2716 if (sys.isValid())
2717 return zoneStateAtMillis(sys, millis, dst);
2718#endif // timezone
2719
2720 // Kludge
2721 // Use a time in the system range with the same day-of-week pattern to its year:
2722 auto fake = millisToWithinRange(millis);
2723 if (Q_LIKELY(fake.good)) {
2724 auto result = QLocalTime::mapLocalTime(local: fake.shifted, dst);
2725 if (result.valid) {
2726 qint64 adjusted;
2727 if (Q_UNLIKELY(add_overflow(result.when, millis - fake.shifted, &adjusted))) {
2728 using Bound = std::numeric_limits<qint64>;
2729 adjusted = millis < fake.shifted ? Bound::min() : Bound::max();
2730 }
2731 result.when = adjusted;
2732 } else {
2733 result.when = millis;
2734 }
2735 return result;
2736 }
2737 // Overflow, apparently.
2738 return {millis};
2739}
2740
2741#if QT_CONFIG(timezone)
2742// For a TimeZone and a time expressed in zone msecs encoding, possibly with a
2743// hint to DST-ness, compute the actual DST-ness and offset, adjusting the time
2744// if needed to escape a spring-forward.
2745QDateTimePrivate::ZoneState QDateTimePrivate::zoneStateAtMillis(const QTimeZone &zone,
2746 qint64 millis, DaylightStatus dst)
2747{
2748 Q_ASSERT(zone.isValid());
2749 Q_ASSERT(zone.timeSpec() == Qt::TimeZone);
2750 // Get the effective data from QTimeZone
2751 QTimeZonePrivate::Data data = zone.d->dataForLocalTime(millis, int(dst));
2752 if (data.offsetFromUtc == QTimeZonePrivate::invalidSeconds())
2753 return {millis};
2754 Q_ASSERT(zone.d->offsetFromUtc(data.atMSecsSinceEpoch) == data.offsetFromUtc);
2755 ZoneState state(data.atMSecsSinceEpoch + data.offsetFromUtc * MSECS_PER_SEC,
2756 data.offsetFromUtc,
2757 data.daylightTimeOffset ? DaylightTime : StandardTime);
2758 // Revise offset, when stepping out of a spring-forward, to what makes a
2759 // fromMSecsSinceEpoch(toMSecsSinceEpoch()) of the resulting QDT work:
2760 if (millis != state.when)
2761 state.offset += (millis - state.when) / MSECS_PER_SEC;
2762 return state;
2763}
2764#endif // timezone

2766static inline QDateTimePrivate::ZoneState stateAtMillis(QTimeZone zone, qint64 millis,
2767 QDateTimePrivate::DaylightStatus dst)
2768{
2769 if (zone.timeSpec() == Qt::LocalTime)
2770 return QDateTimePrivate::localStateAtMillis(millis, dst);
2771#if QT_CONFIG(timezone)
2772 if (zone.timeSpec() == Qt::TimeZone && zone.isValid())
2773 return QDateTimePrivate::zoneStateAtMillis(zone, millis, dst);
2774#endif
2775 return {millis};
2776}

2855/* True if we *can cheaply determine* that a and b use the same offset.
2856 If they use different offsets or it would be expensive to find out, false.
2857 Calls to toMSecsSinceEpoch() are expensive, for these purposes.
2858 See QDateTime's comparison operators.
2859*/
2860static inline bool usesSameOffset(const QDateTimeData &a, const QDateTimeData &b)
2861{
2862 const auto status = getStatus(d: a);
2863 if (status != getStatus(d: b))
2864 return false;
2865 // Status includes DST-ness, so we now know they match in it.
2866
2867 switch (extractSpec(status)) {
2868 case Qt::LocalTime:
2869 case Qt::UTC:
2870 return true;
2871
2872 case Qt::TimeZone:
2873 /* TimeZone always determines its offset during construction of the
2874 private data. Even if we're in different zones, what matters is the
2875 offset actually in effect at the specific time. (DST can cause things
2876 with the same time-zone to use different offsets, but we already
2877 checked their DSTs match.) */
2878 case Qt::OffsetFromUTC: // always knows its offset, which is all that matters.
2879 Q_ASSERT(!a.isShort() && !b.isShort());
2880 return a->m_offsetFromUtc == b->m_offsetFromUtc;
2881 }
2882 Q_UNREACHABLE_RETURN(false);
2883}

2885// Refresh the LocalTime or TimeZone validity and offset
2886static void refreshZonedDateTime(QDateTimeData &d, const QTimeZone &zone)
2887{
2888 Q_ASSERT(zone.timeSpec() == Qt::TimeZone || zone.timeSpec() == Qt::LocalTime);
2889 auto status = getStatus(d);
2890 Q_ASSERT(extractSpec(status) == zone.timeSpec());
2891 int offsetFromUtc = 0;
2892
2893 // If not valid date and time then is invalid
2894 if (!status.testFlags(flags: QDateTimePrivate::ValidDate | QDateTimePrivate::ValidTime)) {
2895 status.setFlag(flag: QDateTimePrivate::ValidDateTime, on: false);
2896 } else {
2897 // We have a valid date and time and a Qt::LocalTime or Qt::TimeZone that needs calculating
2898 // LocalTime and TimeZone might fall into a "missing" DST transition hour
2899 // Calling toEpochMSecs will adjust the returned date/time if it does
2900 qint64 msecs = getMSecs(d);
2901 QDateTimePrivate::ZoneState state = stateAtMillis(zone, millis: msecs,
2902 dst: extractDaylightStatus(status));
2903 // Save the offset to use in offsetFromUtc() &c., even if the next check
2904 // marks invalid; this lets fromMSecsSinceEpoch() give a useful fallback
2905 // for times in spring-forward gaps.
2906 offsetFromUtc = state.offset;
2907 Q_ASSERT(!state.valid || (state.offset >= -SECS_PER_DAY && state.offset <= SECS_PER_DAY));
2908 if (state.valid && msecs == state.when)
2909 status = mergeDaylightStatus(sf: status | QDateTimePrivate::ValidDateTime, status: state.dst);
2910 else // msecs changed or failed to convert (e.g. overflow)
2911 status.setFlag(flag: QDateTimePrivate::ValidDateTime, on: false);
2912 }
2913
2914 if (status.testFlag(flag: QDateTimePrivate::ShortData)) {
2915 d.data.status = status.toInt();
2916 } else {
2917 d->m_status = status;
2918 d->m_offsetFromUtc = offsetFromUtc;
2919 }
2920}
2921
2922// Check the UTC / offsetFromUTC validity
2923static void refreshSimpleDateTime(QDateTimeData &d)
2924{
2925 auto status = getStatus(d);
2926 Q_ASSERT(QTimeZone::isUtcOrFixedOffset(extractSpec(status)));
2927 status.setFlag(flag: QDateTimePrivate::ValidDateTime,
2928 on: status.testFlags(flags: QDateTimePrivate::ValidDate | QDateTimePrivate::ValidTime));
2929
2930 if (status.testFlag(flag: QDateTimePrivate::ShortData))
2931 d.data.status = status.toInt();
2932 else
2933 d->m_status = status;
2934}

2936// Clean up and set status after assorted set-up or reworking:
2937static void checkValidDateTime(QDateTimeData &d)
2938{
2939 auto spec = extractSpec(status: getStatus(d));
2940 switch (spec) {
2941 case Qt::OffsetFromUTC:
2942 case Qt::UTC:
2943 // for these, a valid date and a valid time imply a valid QDateTime
2944 refreshSimpleDateTime(d);
2945 break;
2946 case Qt::TimeZone:
2947 case Qt::LocalTime:
2948 // For these, we need to check whether (the zone is valid and) the time
2949 // is valid for the zone. Expensive, but we have no other option.
2950 refreshZonedDateTime(d, zone: d.timeZone());
2951 break;
2952 }
2953}

2955static void reviseTimeZone(QDateTimeData &d, QTimeZone zone)
2956{
2957 Qt::TimeSpec spec = zone.timeSpec();
2958 auto status = mergeSpec(status: getStatus(d), spec);
2959 bool reuse = d.isShort();
2960 int offset = 0;
2961
2962 switch (spec) {
2963 case Qt::UTC:
2964 Q_ASSERT(zone.fixedSecondsAheadOfUtc() == 0);
2965 break;
2966 case Qt::OffsetFromUTC:
2967 reuse = false;
2968 offset = zone.fixedSecondsAheadOfUtc();
2969 Q_ASSERT(offset);
2970 break;
2971 case Qt::TimeZone:
2972 reuse = false;
2973 break;
2974 case Qt::LocalTime:
2975 break;
2976 }
2977
2978 status &= ~(QDateTimePrivate::ValidDateTime | QDateTimePrivate::DaylightMask);
2979 if (reuse) {
2980 d.data.status = status.toInt();
2981 } else {
2982 d.detach();
2983 d->m_status = status & ~QDateTimePrivate::ShortData;
2984 d->m_offsetFromUtc = offset;
2985#if QT_CONFIG(timezone)
2986 if (spec == Qt::TimeZone)
2987 d->m_timeZone = zone;
2988#endif // timezone
2989 }
2990
2991 if (QTimeZone::isUtcOrFixedOffset(spec))
2992 refreshSimpleDateTime(d);
2993 else
2994 refreshZonedDateTime(d, zone);
2995}

2997static void setDateTime(QDateTimeData &d, QDate date, QTime time)
2998{
2999 // If the date is valid and the time is not we set time to 00:00:00
3000 if (!time.isValid() && date.isValid())
3001 time = QTime::fromMSecsSinceStartOfDay(msecs: 0);
3002
3003 QDateTimePrivate::StatusFlags newStatus = { };
3004
3005 // Set date value and status
3006 qint64 days = 0;
3007 if (date.isValid()) {
3008 days = date.toJulianDay() - JULIAN_DAY_FOR_EPOCH;
3009 newStatus = QDateTimePrivate::ValidDate;
3010 }
3011
3012 // Set time value and status
3013 int ds = 0;
3014 if (time.isValid()) {
3015 ds = time.msecsSinceStartOfDay();
3016 newStatus |= QDateTimePrivate::ValidTime;
3017 }
3018 Q_ASSERT(ds < MSECS_PER_DAY);
3019 // Only the later parts of the very first day are representable - its start
3020 // would overflow - so get ds the same side of 0 as days:
3021 if (days < 0 && ds > 0) {
3022 days++;
3023 ds -= MSECS_PER_DAY;
3024 }
3025
3026 // Check in representable range:
3027 qint64 msecs = 0;
3028 if (daysAndMillisOverflow(days, millisInDay: qint64(ds), sumMillis: &msecs)) {
3029 newStatus = QDateTimePrivate::StatusFlags{};
3030 msecs = 0;
3031 }
3032 if (d.isShort()) {
3033 // let's see if we can keep this short
3034 if (msecsCanBeSmall(msecs)) {
3035 // yes, we can
3036 d.data.msecs = qintptr(msecs);
3037 d.data.status &= ~(QDateTimePrivate::ValidityMask | QDateTimePrivate::DaylightMask).toInt();
3038 d.data.status |= newStatus.toInt();
3039 } else {
3040 // nope...
3041 d.detach();
3042 }
3043 }
3044 if (!d.isShort()) {
3045 d.detach();
3046 d->m_msecs = msecs;
3047 d->m_status &= ~(QDateTimePrivate::ValidityMask | QDateTimePrivate::DaylightMask);
3048 d->m_status |= newStatus;
3049 }
3050}

3052static QPair<QDate, QTime> getDateTime(const QDateTimeData &d)
3053{
3054 auto status = getStatus(d);
3055 const qint64 msecs = getMSecs(d);
3056 const qint64 days = QRoundingDown::qDiv(a: msecs, b: MSECS_PER_DAY);
3057 return { status.testFlag(flag: QDateTimePrivate::ValidDate)
3058 ? QDate::fromJulianDay(jd_: JULIAN_DAY_FOR_EPOCH + days)
3059 : QDate(),
3060 status.testFlag(flag: QDateTimePrivate::ValidTime)
3061 ? QTime::fromMSecsSinceStartOfDay(msecs: msecs - days * MSECS_PER_DAY)
3062 : QTime() };
3063}

3244/*!
3245 \class QDateTime
3246 \inmodule QtCore
3247 \ingroup shared
3248 \reentrant
3249 \brief The QDateTime class provides date and time functions.
3250
3251 A QDateTime object encodes a calendar date and a clock time (a "datetime")
3252 in accordance with a time representation. It combines features of the QDate
3253 and QTime classes. It can read the current datetime from the system
3254 clock. It provides functions for comparing datetimes and for manipulating a
3255 datetime by adding a number of seconds, days, months, or years.
3256
3257 QDateTime can describe datetimes with respect to \l{Qt::LocalTime}{local
3258 time}, to \l{Qt::UTC}{UTC}, to a specified \l{Qt::OffsetFromUTC}{offset from
3259 UTC} or to a specified \l{Qt::TimeZone}{time zone}. Each of these time
3260 representations can be encapsulated in a suitable instance of the QTimeZone
3261 class. For example, a time zone of "Europe/Berlin" will apply the
3262 daylight-saving rules as used in Germany. In contrast, a fixed offset from
3263 UTC of +3600 seconds is one hour ahead of UTC (usually written in ISO
3264 standard notation as "UTC+01:00"), with no daylight-saving
3265 complications. When using either local time or a specified time zone,
3266 time-zone transitions (see \l {Daylight-Saving Time (DST)}{below}) are taken
3267 into account. A QDateTime's timeSpec() will tell you which of the four types
3268 of time representation is in use; its timeRepresentation() provides a full
3269 representation of that time representation, as a QTimeZone.
3270
3271 A QDateTime object is typically created either by giving a date and time
3272 explicitly in the constructor, or by using a static function such as
3273 currentDateTime() or fromMSecsSinceEpoch(). The date and time can be changed
3274 with setDate() and setTime(). A datetime can also be set using the
3275 setMSecsSinceEpoch() function that takes the time, in milliseconds, since
3276 the start, in UTC of the year 1970. The fromString() function returns a
3277 QDateTime, given a string and a date format used to interpret the date
3278 within the string.
3279
3280 QDateTime::currentDateTime() returns a QDateTime that expresses the current
3281 date and time with respect to a specific time representation, such as local
3282 time (its default). QDateTime::currentDateTimeUtc() returns a QDateTime that
3283 expresses the current date and time with respect to UTC; it is equivalent to
3284 \c {QDateTime::currentDateTime(QTimeZone::UTC)}.
3285
3286 The date() and time() functions provide access to the date and
3287 time parts of the datetime. The same information is provided in
3288 textual format by the toString() function.
3289
3290 QDateTime provides a full set of operators to compare two
3291 QDateTime objects, where smaller means earlier and larger means
3292 later.
3293
3294 You can increment (or decrement) a datetime by a given number of
3295 milliseconds using addMSecs(), seconds using addSecs(), or days using
3296 addDays(). Similarly, you can use addMonths() and addYears(). The daysTo()
3297 function returns the number of days between two datetimes, secsTo() returns
3298 the number of seconds between two datetimes, and msecsTo() returns the
3299 number of milliseconds between two datetimes. These operations are aware of
3300 daylight-saving time (DST) and other time-zone transitions, where
3301 applicable.
3302
3303 Use toTimeZone() to re-express a datetime in terms of a different time
3304 representation. By passing a lightweight QTimeZone that represents local
3305 time, UTC or a fixed offset from UTC, you can convert the datetime to use
3306 the corresponding time representation; or you can pass a full time zone
3307 (whose \l {QTimeZone::timeSpec()}{timeSpec()} is \c {Qt::TimeZone}) to use
3308 that instead.
3309
3310 \note QDateTime does not account for leap seconds.
3311
3312 \section1 Remarks
3313
3314 \note All conversion to and from string formats is done using the C locale.
3315 For localized conversions, see QLocale.
3316
3317 \note There is no year 0 in the Gregorian calendar. Dates in that year are
3318 considered invalid. The year -1 is the year "1 before Christ" or "1 before
3319 common era." The day before 1 January 1 CE is 31 December 1 BCE.
3320
3321 \section2 Range of Valid Dates
3322
3323 The range of values that QDateTime can represent is dependent on the
3324 internal storage implementation. QDateTime is currently stored in a qint64
3325 as a serial msecs value encoding the date and time. This restricts the date
3326 range to about +/- 292 million years, compared to the QDate range of +/- 2
3327 billion years. Care must be taken when creating a QDateTime with extreme
3328 values that you do not overflow the storage. The exact range of supported
3329 values varies depending on the time representation used.
3330
3331 \section2 Use of Timezones
3332
3333 QDateTime uses the system's time zone information to determine the current
3334 local time zone and its offset from UTC. If the system is not configured
3335 correctly or not up-to-date, QDateTime will give wrong results.
3336
3337 QDateTime likewise uses system-provided information to determine the offsets
3338 of other timezones from UTC. If this information is incomplete or out of
3339 date, QDateTime will give wrong results. See the QTimeZone documentation for
3340 more details.
3341
3342 On modern Unix systems, this means QDateTime usually has accurate
3343 information about historical transitions (including DST, see below) whenever
3344 possible. On Windows, where the system doesn't support historical timezone
3345 data, historical accuracy is not maintained with respect to timezone
3346 transitions, notably including DST. However, building Qt with the ICU
3347 library will equipe QTimeZone with the same timezone database as is used on
3348 Unix.
3349
3350 \section2 Daylight-Saving Time (DST)
3351
3352 QDateTime takes into account transitions between Standard Time and
3353 Daylight-Saving Time. For example, if the transition is at 2am and the clock
3354 goes forward to 3am, then there is a "missing" hour from 02:00:00 to
3355 02:59:59.999 which QDateTime considers to be invalid. Any date arithmetic
3356 performed will take this missing hour into account and return a valid
3357 result. For example, adding one second to 01:59:59 will get 03:00:00.
3358
3359 For datetimes that the system \c time_t can represent (from 1901-12-14 to
3360 2038-01-18 on systems with 32-bit \c time_t; for the full range QDateTime
3361 can represent if the type is 64-bit), the standard system APIs are used to
3362 determine local time's offset from UTC. For datetimes not handled by these
3363 system APIs, QTimeZone::systemTimeZone() is used. In either case, the offset
3364 information used depends on the system and may be incomplete or, for past
3365 times, historically inaccurate. In any case, for future dates, the local
3366 time zone's offsets and DST rules may change before that date comes around.
3367
3368 \section2 Offsets From UTC
3369
3370 Offsets from UTC are measured in seconds east of Greenwich. The moment
3371 described by a particular date and time, such as noon on a particular day,
3372 depends on the time representation used. Those with a higher offset from UTC
3373 describe an earlier moment, and those with a lower offset a later moment, by
3374 any given combination of date and time.
3375
3376 There is no explicit size restriction on an offset from UTC, but there is an
3377 implicit limit imposed when using the toString() and fromString() methods
3378 which use a [+|-]hh:mm format, effectively limiting the range to +/- 99
3379 hours and 59 minutes and whole minutes only. Note that currently no time
3380 zone has an offset outside the range of ±14 hours and all known offsets are
3381 multiples of five minutes.
3382
3383 \sa QDate, QTime, QDateTimeEdit, QTimeZone
3384*/
3385
3386/*!
3387 \since 5.14
3388 \enum QDateTime::YearRange
3389
3390 This enumerated type describes the range of years (in the Gregorian
3391 calendar) representable by QDateTime:
3392
3393 \value First The later parts of this year are representable
3394 \value Last The earlier parts of this year are representable
3395
3396 All dates strictly between these two years are also representable.
3397 Note, however, that the Gregorian Calendar has no year zero.
3398
3399 \note QDate can describe dates in a wider range of years. For most
3400 purposes, this makes little difference, as the range of years that QDateTime
3401 can support reaches 292 million years either side of 1970.
3402
3403 \sa isValid(), QDate
3404*/
3405

3630/*!
3631 \since 5.2
3632
3633 Returns this datetime's Offset From UTC in seconds.
3634
3635 The result depends on timeSpec():
3636 \list
3637 \li \c Qt::UTC The offset is 0.
3638 \li \c Qt::OffsetFromUTC The offset is the value originally set.
3639 \li \c Qt::LocalTime The local time's offset from UTC is returned.
3640 \li \c Qt::TimeZone The offset used by the time-zone is returned.
3641 \endlist
3642
3643 For the last two, the offset at this date and time will be returned, taking
3644 account of Daylight-Saving Offset. The offset is the difference between the
3645 local time or time in the given time-zone and UTC time; it is positive in
3646 time-zones ahead of UTC (East of The Prime Meridian), negative for those
3647 behind UTC (West of The Prime Meridian).
3648
3649 \sa setOffsetFromUtc()
3650*/
3651
3652int QDateTime::offsetFromUtc() const
3653{
3654 if (!d.isShort())
3655 return d->m_offsetFromUtc;
3656 if (!isValid())
3657 return 0;
3658
3659 auto spec = getSpec(d);
3660 if (spec == Qt::LocalTime) {
3661 // we didn't cache the value, so we need to calculate it now...
3662 qint64 msecs = getMSecs(d);
3663 return (msecs - toMSecsSinceEpoch()) / MSECS_PER_SEC;
3664 }
3665
3666 Q_ASSERT(spec == Qt::UTC);
3667 return 0;
3668}

3670/*!
3671 \since 5.2
3672
3673 Returns the Time Zone Abbreviation for this datetime.
3674
3675 The returned string depends on timeSpec():
3676
3677 \list
3678 \li For Qt::UTC it is "UTC".
3679 \li For Qt::OffsetFromUTC it will be in the format "UTC[+-]00:00".
3680 \li For Qt::LocalTime, the host system is queried.
3681 \li For Qt::TimeZone, the associated QTimeZone object is queried.
3682 \endlist
3683
3684 \note The abbreviation is not guaranteed to be unique, i.e. different time
3685 zones may have the same abbreviation. For Qt::LocalTime and Qt::TimeZone,
3686 when returned by the host system, the abbreviation may be localized.
3687
3688 \sa timeSpec(), QTimeZone::abbreviation()
3689*/
3690
3691QString QDateTime::timeZoneAbbreviation() const
3692{
3693 if (!isValid())
3694 return QString();
3695
3696 switch (getSpec(d)) {
3697 case Qt::UTC:
3698 return "UTC"_L1;
3699 case Qt::OffsetFromUTC:
3700 return "UTC"_L1 + toOffsetString(format: Qt::ISODate, offset: d->m_offsetFromUtc);
3701 case Qt::TimeZone:
3702#if !QT_CONFIG(timezone)
3703 break;
3704#else
3705 Q_ASSERT(d->m_timeZone.isValid());
3706 return d->m_timeZone.abbreviation(*this);
3707#endif // timezone
3708 case Qt::LocalTime:
3709 return QDateTimePrivate::localNameAtMillis(millis: getMSecs(d),
3710 dst: extractDaylightStatus(status: getStatus(d)));
3711 }
3712 return QString();
3713}
