3715/*!
3716 \since 5.2
3717
3718 Returns if this datetime falls in Daylight-Saving Time.
3719
3720 If the Qt::TimeSpec is not Qt::LocalTime or Qt::TimeZone then will always
3721 return false.
3722
3723 \sa timeSpec()
3724*/
3725
3726bool QDateTime::isDaylightTime() const
3727{
3728 if (!isValid())
3729 return false;
3730
3731 switch (getSpec(d)) {
3732 case Qt::UTC:
3733 case Qt::OffsetFromUTC:
3734 return false;
3735 case Qt::TimeZone:
3736#if !QT_CONFIG(timezone)
3737 break;
3738#else
3739 Q_ASSERT(d->m_timeZone.isValid());
3740 if (auto dst = extractDaylightStatus(getStatus(d));
3741 dst != QDateTimePrivate::UnknownDaylightTime) {
3742 return dst == QDateTimePrivate::DaylightTime;
3743 }
3744 return d->m_timeZone.d->isDaylightTime(toMSecsSinceEpoch());
3745#endif // timezone
3746 case Qt::LocalTime: {
3747 auto dst = extractDaylightStatus(status: getStatus(d));
3748 if (dst == QDateTimePrivate::UnknownDaylightTime)
3749 dst = QDateTimePrivate::localStateAtMillis(millis: getMSecs(d), dst).dst;
3750 return dst == QDateTimePrivate::DaylightTime;
3751 }
3752 }
3753 return false;
3754}

3854/*!
3855 \since 4.7
3856
3857 Returns the datetime as a number of milliseconds after the start, in UTC, of
3858 the year 1970.
3859
3860 On systems that do not support time zones, this function will
3861 behave as if local time were Qt::UTC.
3862
3863 The behavior for this function is undefined if the datetime stored in
3864 this object is not valid. However, for all valid dates, this function
3865 returns a unique value.
3866
3867 \sa toSecsSinceEpoch(), setMSecsSinceEpoch(), fromMSecsSinceEpoch()
3868*/
3869qint64 QDateTime::toMSecsSinceEpoch() const
3870{
3871 // Note: QDateTimeParser relies on this producing a useful result, even when
3872 // !isValid(), at least when the invalidity is a time in a fall-back (that
3873 // we'll have adjusted to lie outside it, but marked invalid because it's
3874 // not what was asked for). Other things may be doing similar.
3875 switch (getSpec(d)) {
3876 case Qt::UTC:
3877 return getMSecs(d);
3878
3879 case Qt::OffsetFromUTC:
3880 Q_ASSERT(!d.isShort());
3881 return d->m_msecs - d->m_offsetFromUtc * MSECS_PER_SEC;
3882
3883 case Qt::LocalTime:
3884 if (d.isShort()) {
3885 // Short form has nowhere to cache the offset, so recompute.
3886 auto dst = extractDaylightStatus(status: getStatus(d));
3887 auto state = QDateTimePrivate::localStateAtMillis(millis: getMSecs(d), dst);
3888 return state.when - state.offset * MSECS_PER_SEC;
3889 }
3890 // Use the offset saved by refreshZonedDateTime() on creation.
3891 return d->m_msecs - d->m_offsetFromUtc * MSECS_PER_SEC;
3892
3893 case Qt::TimeZone:
3894 Q_ASSERT(!d.isShort());
3895#if QT_CONFIG(timezone)
3896 // Use offset refreshZonedDateTime() saved on creation:
3897 if (d->m_timeZone.isValid())
3898 return d->m_msecs - d->m_offsetFromUtc * MSECS_PER_SEC;
3899#endif
3900 return 0;
3901 }
3902 Q_UNREACHABLE_RETURN(0);
3903}
3904
3905/*!
3906 \since 5.8
3907
3908 Returns the datetime as a number of seconds after the start, in UTC, of the
3909 year 1970.
3910
3911 On systems that do not support time zones, this function will
3912 behave as if local time were Qt::UTC.
3913
3914 The behavior for this function is undefined if the datetime stored in
3915 this object is not valid. However, for all valid dates, this function
3916 returns a unique value.
3917
3918 \sa toMSecsSinceEpoch(), fromSecsSinceEpoch(), setSecsSinceEpoch()
3919*/
3920qint64 QDateTime::toSecsSinceEpoch() const
3921{
3922 return toMSecsSinceEpoch() / MSECS_PER_SEC;
3923}
3924
3925/*!
3926 \since 4.7
3927
3928 Sets the datetime to represent a moment a given number, \a msecs, of
3929 milliseconds after the start, in UTC, of the year 1970.
3930
3931 On systems that do not support time zones, this function will
3932 behave as if local time were Qt::UTC.
3933
3934 Note that passing the minimum of \c qint64
3935 (\c{std::numeric_limits<qint64>::min()}) to \a msecs will result in
3936 undefined behavior.
3937
3938 \sa setSecsSinceEpoch(), toMSecsSinceEpoch(), fromMSecsSinceEpoch()
3939*/
3940void QDateTime::setMSecsSinceEpoch(qint64 msecs)
3941{
3942 auto status = getStatus(d);
3943 const auto spec = extractSpec(status);
3944 Q_ASSERT(specCanBeSmall(spec) || !d.isShort());
3945 QDateTimePrivate::ZoneState state(msecs);
3946
3947 status &= ~QDateTimePrivate::ValidityMask;
3948 if (QTimeZone::isUtcOrFixedOffset(spec)) {
3949 if (spec == Qt::OffsetFromUTC)
3950 state.offset = d->m_offsetFromUtc;
3951 if (!state.offset || !add_overflow(v1: msecs, v2: state.offset * MSECS_PER_SEC, r: &state.when))
3952 status |= QDateTimePrivate::ValidityMask;
3953 } else if (spec == Qt::LocalTime) {
3954 state = QDateTimePrivate::expressUtcAsLocal(utcMSecs: msecs);
3955 if (state.valid)
3956 status = mergeDaylightStatus(sf: status | QDateTimePrivate::ValidityMask, status: state.dst);
3957#if QT_CONFIG(timezone)
3958 } else if (spec == Qt::TimeZone && (d.detach(), d->m_timeZone.isValid())) {
3959 const auto data = d->m_timeZone.d->data(msecs);
3960 if (Q_LIKELY(data.offsetFromUtc != QTimeZonePrivate::invalidSeconds())) {
3961 state.offset = data.offsetFromUtc;
3962 Q_ASSERT(state.offset >= -SECS_PER_DAY && state.offset <= SECS_PER_DAY);
3963 if (!state.offset
3964 || !Q_UNLIKELY(add_overflow(msecs, state.offset * MSECS_PER_SEC, &state.when))) {
3965 d->m_status = mergeDaylightStatus(status | QDateTimePrivate::ValidityMask,
3966 data.daylightTimeOffset
3967 ? QDateTimePrivate::DaylightTime
3968 : QDateTimePrivate::StandardTime);
3969 d->m_msecs = state.when;
3970 d->m_offsetFromUtc = state.offset;
3971 return;
3972 } // else: zone can't represent this UTC time
3973 } // else: zone unable to represent given UTC time (should only happen on overflow).
3974#endif // timezone
3975 }
3976 Q_ASSERT(!status.testFlag(QDateTimePrivate::ValidDateTime)
3977 || (state.offset >= -SECS_PER_DAY && state.offset <= SECS_PER_DAY));
3978
3979 if (msecsCanBeSmall(msecs: state.when) && d.isShort()) {

4018
4019 Returns the datetime as a string in the \a format given.
4020
4021 If the \a format is Qt::TextDate, the string is formatted in the default
4022 way. The day and month names will be in English. An example of this

4033 date, use the \a format Qt::ISODateWithMs, which corresponds to
4034 yyyy-MM-ddTHH:mm:ss.zzz[Z|[+|-]HH:mm].

4037 following \l{RFC 2822}.
4038

4042 range 0 to 9999.
4043
4044 \sa fromString(), QDate::toString(), QTime::toString(),
4045 QLocale::toString()
4046*/
4047QString QDateTime::toString(Qt::DateFormat format) const
4048{

4050 if (!isValid())
4051 return buf;
4052
4053 switch (format) {
4054 case Qt::RFC2822Date:
4055 buf = QLocale::c().toString(dateTime: *this, format: u"dd MMM yyyy hh:mm:ss ");
4056 buf += toOffsetString(format: Qt::TextDate, offset: offsetFromUtc());
4057 return buf;
4058 default:
4059 case Qt::TextDate: {
4060 const QPair<QDate, QTime> p = getDateTime(d);
4061 buf = toStringTextDate(date: p.first);
4062 // Insert time between date's day and year:
4063 buf.insert(i: buf.lastIndexOf(c: u' '),
4064 s: u' ' + p.second.toString(format: Qt::TextDate));
4065 // Append zone/offset indicator, as appropriate:
4066 switch (timeSpec()) {
4067 case Qt::LocalTime:
4068 break;
4069#if QT_CONFIG(timezone)
4070 case Qt::TimeZone:
4071 buf += u' ' + d->m_timeZone.displayName(
4072 *this, QTimeZone::OffsetName, QLocale::c());
4073 break;
4074#endif
4075 default:
4076#if 0 // ### Qt 7 GMT: use UTC instead, see qnamespace.qdoc documentation
4077 buf += " UTC"_L1;
4078#else
4079 buf += " GMT"_L1;
4080#endif
4081 if (getSpec(d) == Qt::OffsetFromUTC)
4082 buf += toOffsetString(format: Qt::TextDate, offset: offsetFromUtc());
4083 }
4084 return buf;
4085 }
4086 case Qt::ISODate:
4087 case Qt::ISODateWithMs: {
4088 const QPair<QDate, QTime> p = getDateTime(d);
4089 buf = toStringIsoDate(date: p.first);
4090 if (buf.isEmpty())
4091 return QString(); // failed to convert
4092 buf += u'T' + p.second.toString(format);
4093 switch (getSpec(d)) {
4094 case Qt::UTC:
4095 buf += u'Z';
4096 break;
4097 case Qt::OffsetFromUTC:
4098 case Qt::TimeZone:
4099 buf += toOffsetString(format: Qt::ISODate, offset: offsetFromUtc());
4100 break;
4101 default:
4102 break;
4103 }
4104 return buf;
4105 }
4106 }

4156static inline void massageAdjustedDateTime(QDateTimeData &d, QDate date, QTime time)
4157{
4158 /*
4159 If we have just adjusted to a day with a DST transition, our given time
4160 may lie in the transition hour (either missing or duplicated). For any
4161 other time, telling mktime() or QTimeZone what we know about DST-ness, of
4162 the time we adjusted from, will make no difference; it'll just tell us the
4163 actual DST-ness of the given time. When landing in a transition that
4164 repeats an hour, passing the prior DST-ness - when known - will get us the
4165 indicated side of the duplicate (either local or zone). When landing in a
4166 gap, the zone gives us the other side of the gap and mktime() is wrapped
4167 to coax it into doing the same (which it does by default on Unix).
4168 */
4169 auto status = getStatus(d);
4170 Q_ASSERT(status.testFlags(QDateTimePrivate::ValidDate | QDateTimePrivate::ValidTime
4171 | QDateTimePrivate::ValidDateTime));
4172 auto spec = extractSpec(status);
4173 if (QTimeZone::isUtcOrFixedOffset(spec)) {
4174 setDateTime(d, date, time);
4175 refreshSimpleDateTime(d);
4176 return;
4177 }
4178 auto dst = extractDaylightStatus(status);
4179 qint64 local = timeToMSecs(date, time);
4180 const QDateTimePrivate::ZoneState state = stateAtMillis(zone: d.timeZone(), millis: local, dst);
4181 if (state.valid)
4182 status = mergeDaylightStatus(sf: status | QDateTimePrivate::ValidDateTime, status: state.dst);
4183 else
4184 status.setFlag(flag: QDateTimePrivate::ValidDateTime, on: false);
4185
4186 if (status & QDateTimePrivate::ShortData) {
4187 d.data.msecs = state.when;
4188 d.data.status = status.toInt();
4189 } else {
4190 d.detach();
4191 d->m_status = status;
4192 if (state.valid) {
4193 d->m_msecs = state.when;
4194 d->m_offsetFromUtc = state.offset;
4195 }
4196 }
4197}

4292/*!
4293 Returns a QDateTime object containing a datetime \a msecs milliseconds
4294 later than the datetime of this object (or earlier if \a msecs is
4295 negative).
4296
4297 If this datetime is invalid, an invalid datetime will be returned.
4298
4299 \sa addSecs(), msecsTo(), addDays(), addMonths(), addYears()
4300*/
4301QDateTime QDateTime::addMSecs(qint64 msecs) const
4302{
4303 if (!isValid())
4304 return QDateTime();
4305
4306 QDateTime dt(*this);
4307 switch (getSpec(d)) {
4308 case Qt::LocalTime:
4309 case Qt::TimeZone:
4310 // Convert to real UTC first in case this crosses a DST transition:
4311 if (!add_overflow(v1: toMSecsSinceEpoch(), v2: msecs, r: &msecs)) {
4312 dt.setMSecsSinceEpoch(msecs);
4313 } else if (dt.d.isShort()) {
4314 dt.d.data.status &= ~int(QDateTimePrivate::ValidityMask);
4315 } else {
4316 dt.d.detach();
4317 dt.d->m_status &= ~QDateTimePrivate::ValidityMask;
4318 }
4319 break;
4320 case Qt::UTC:
4321 case Qt::OffsetFromUTC:
4322 // No need to convert, just add on
4323 if (add_overflow(v1: getMSecs(d), v2: msecs, r: &msecs)) {
4324 if (dt.d.isShort()) {
4325 dt.d.data.status &= ~int(QDateTimePrivate::ValidityMask);
4326 } else {
4327 dt.d.detach();
4328 dt.d->m_status &= ~QDateTimePrivate::ValidityMask;
4329 }
4330 } else if (d.isShort()) {
4331 // need to check if we need to enlarge first
4332 if (msecsCanBeSmall(msecs)) {
4333 dt.d.data.msecs = qintptr(msecs);
4334 } else {
4335 dt.d.detach();
4336 dt.d->m_msecs = msecs;
4337 }
4338 } else {
4339 dt.d.detach();
4340 dt.d->m_msecs = msecs;
4341 }
4342 break;
4343 }
4344 return dt;
4345}

4657/*!
4658 \internal
4659 Returns \c true if \a lhs is earlier than the \a rhs
4660 datetime; otherwise returns \c false.
4661
4662 \sa equals(), operator<()
4663*/
4664
4665bool QDateTime::precedes(const QDateTime &other) const
4666{
4667 if (!isValid())
4668 return other.isValid();
4669 if (!other.isValid())
4670 return false;
4671
4672 if (usesSameOffset(a: d, b: other.d))
4673 return getMSecs(d) < getMSecs(d: other.d);
4674
4675 // Convert to UTC and compare
4676 return toMSecsSinceEpoch() < other.toMSecsSinceEpoch();
4677}

5069
5070/*!
5071 \fn QDateTime QDateTime::fromString(const QString &string, Qt::DateFormat format)
5072
5073 Returns the QDateTime represented by the \a string, using the
5074 \a format given, or an invalid datetime if this is not possible.
5075
5076 Note for Qt::TextDate: only English short month names (e.g. "Jan" in short
5077 form or "January" in long form) are recognized.
5078
5079 \sa toString(), QLocale::toDateTime()
5080*/
5081
5082/*!
5083 \overload
5084 \since 6.0
5085*/
5086QDateTime QDateTime::fromString(QStringView string, Qt::DateFormat format)
5087{
5088 if (string.isEmpty())
5089 return QDateTime();
5090
5091 switch (format) {
5092 case Qt::RFC2822Date: {
5093 const ParsedRfcDateTime rfc = rfcDateImpl(s: string);
5094
5095 if (!rfc.date.isValid() || !rfc.time.isValid())
5096 return QDateTime();
5097
5098 QDateTime dateTime(rfc.date, rfc.time, QTimeZone::UTC);
5099 dateTime.setTimeZone(QTimeZone::fromSecondsAheadOfUtc(offset: rfc.utcOffset));
5100 return dateTime;
5101 }
5102 case Qt::ISODate:
5103 case Qt::ISODateWithMs: {
5104 const int size = string.size();
5105 if (size < 10)
5106 return QDateTime();
5107
5108 QDate date = QDate::fromString(string: string.first(n: 10), format: Qt::ISODate);
5109 if (!date.isValid())
5110 return QDateTime();
5111 if (size == 10)
5112 return date.startOfDay();
5113
5114 QTimeZone zone = QTimeZone::LocalTime;
5115 QStringView isoString = string.sliced(pos: 10); // trim "yyyy-MM-dd"
5116
5117 // Must be left with T (or space) and at least one digit for the hour:
5118 if (isoString.size() < 2
5119 || !(isoString.startsWith(c: u'T', cs: Qt::CaseInsensitive)
5120 // RFC 3339 (section 5.6) allows a space here. (It actually
5121 // allows any separator one considers more readable, merely
5122 // giving space as an example - but let's not go wild !)
5123 || isoString.startsWith(c: u' '))) {
5124 return QDateTime();
5125 }
5126 isoString = isoString.sliced(pos: 1); // trim 'T' (or space)
5127
5128 // Check end of string for Time Zone definition, either Z for UTC or [+-]HH:mm for Offset
5129 if (isoString.endsWith(c: u'Z', cs: Qt::CaseInsensitive)) {
5130 zone = QTimeZone::UTC;
5131 isoString.chop(n: 1); // trim 'Z'
5132 } else {
5133 // the loop below is faster but functionally equal to:
5134 // const int signIndex = isoString.indexOf(QRegulargExpression(QStringLiteral("[+-]")));
5135 int signIndex = isoString.size() - 1;
5136 Q_ASSERT(signIndex >= 0);
5137 bool found = false;
5138 do {
5139 QChar character(isoString[signIndex]);
5140 found = character == u'+' || character == u'-';
5141 } while (!found && --signIndex >= 0);
5142
5143 if (found) {
5144 bool ok;
5145 int offset = fromOffsetString(offsetString: isoString.sliced(pos: signIndex), valid: &ok);
5146 if (!ok)
5147 return QDateTime();
5148 isoString = isoString.first(n: signIndex);
5149 zone = QTimeZone::fromSecondsAheadOfUtc(offset);
5150 }
5151 }
5152
5153 // Might be end of day (24:00, including variants), which QTime considers invalid.
5154 // ISO 8601 (section 4.2.3) says that 24:00 is equivalent to 00:00 the next day.
5155 bool isMidnight24 = false;
5156 QTime time = fromIsoTimeString(string: isoString, format, isMidnight24: &isMidnight24);
5157 if (!time.isValid())
5158 return QDateTime();
5159 if (isMidnight24) // time is 0:0, but we want the start of next day:
5160 return date.addDays(ndays: 1).startOfDay(zone);
5161 return QDateTime(date, time, zone);
5162 }
5163 case Qt::TextDate: {
5164 QVarLengthArray<QStringView, 6> parts;
5165
5166 auto tokens = string.tokenize(needle: u' ', flags: Qt::SkipEmptyParts);
5167 auto it = tokens.begin();
5168 for (int i = 0; i < 6 && it != tokens.end(); ++i, ++it)
5169 parts.emplace_back(args: *it);
5170
5171 // Documented as "ddd MMM d HH:mm:ss yyyy" with optional offset-suffix;
5172 // and allow time either before or after year.
5173 if (parts.size() < 5 || it != tokens.end())
5174 return QDateTime();
5175
5176 // Year and time can be in either order.
5177 // Guess which by looking for ':' in the time
5178 int yearPart = 3;
5179 int timePart = 3;
5180 if (parts.at(idx: 3).contains(c: u':'))
5181 yearPart = 4;
5182 else if (parts.at(idx: 4).contains(c: u':'))
5183 timePart = 4;
5184 else
5185 return QDateTime();
5186
5187 bool ok = false;
5188 int day = parts.at(idx: 2).toInt(ok: &ok);
5189 int year = ok ? parts.at(idx: yearPart).toInt(ok: &ok) : 0;
5190 int month = fromShortMonthName(monthName: parts.at(idx: 1));
5191 if (!ok || year == 0 || day == 0 || month < 1)
5192 return QDateTime();
5193
5194 const QDate date(year, month, day);
5195 if (!date.isValid())
5196 return QDateTime();
5197
5198 const QTime time = fromIsoTimeString(string: parts.at(idx: timePart), format, isMidnight24: nullptr);
5199 if (!time.isValid())
5200 return QDateTime();
5201
5202 if (parts.size() == 5)
5203 return QDateTime(date, time);
5204
5205 QStringView tz = parts.at(idx: 5);
5206 if (tz.startsWith(s: "UTC"_L1)
5207 // GMT has long been deprecated as an alias for UTC.
5208 || tz.startsWith(s: "GMT"_L1, cs: Qt::CaseInsensitive)) {
5209 tz = tz.sliced(pos: 3);
5210 if (tz.isEmpty())
5211 return QDateTime(date, time, QTimeZone::UTC);
5212
5213 int offset = fromOffsetString(offsetString: tz, valid: &ok);
5214 return ok ? QDateTime(date, time, QTimeZone::fromSecondsAheadOfUtc(offset))
5215 : QDateTime();
5216 }
5217 return QDateTime();
5218 }
5219 }
5220
5221 return QDateTime();
5222}

5224/*!
5225 \fn QDateTime QDateTime::fromString(const QString &string, const QString &format, QCalendar cal)
5226
5227 Returns the QDateTime represented by the \a string, using the \a
5228 format given, or an invalid datetime if the string cannot be parsed.
5229
5230 Uses the calendar \a cal if supplied, else Gregorian.
5231
5232 In addition to the expressions, recognized in the format string to represent
5233 parts of the date and time, by QDate::fromString() and QTime::fromString(),
5234 this method supports:
5235
5236 \table
5237 \header \li Expression \li Output
5238 \row \li t
5239 \li the timezone (offset, name, "Z" or offset with "UTC" prefix)
5240 \row \li tt
5241 \li the timezone in offset format with no colon between hours and
5242 minutes (for example "+0200")
5243 \row \li ttt
5244 \li the timezone in offset format with a colon between hours and
5245 minutes (for example "+02:00")
5246 \row \li tttt
5247 \li the timezone name (for example "Europe/Berlin"). The name
5248 recognized are those known to \l QTimeZone, which may depend on the
5249 operating system in use.
5250 \endtable
5251
5252 If no 't' format specifier is present, the system's local time-zone is used.
5253 For the defaults of all other fields, see QDate::fromString() and QTime::fromString().
5254
5255 For example:
5256
5257 \snippet code/src_corelib_time_qdatetime.cpp 14
5258
5259 All other input characters will be treated as text. Any non-empty sequence
5260 of characters enclosed in single quotes will also be treated (stripped of
5261 the quotes) as text and not be interpreted as expressions.
5262
5263 \snippet code/src_corelib_time_qdatetime.cpp 12
5264
5265 If the format is not satisfied, an invalid QDateTime is returned. If the
5266 format is satisfied but \a string represents an invalid datetime (e.g. in a
5267 gap skipped by a time-zone transition), an invalid QDateTime is returned,
5268 whose toMSecsSinceEpoch() represents a near-by datetime that is
5269 valid. Passing that to fromMSecsSinceEpoch() will produce a valid datetime
5270 that isn't faithfully represented by the string parsed.
5271
5272 The expressions that don't have leading zeroes (d, M, h, m, s, z) will be
5273 greedy. This means that they will use two digits (or three, for z) even if this will
5274 put them outside the range and/or leave too few digits for other
5275 sections.
5276
5277 \snippet code/src_corelib_time_qdatetime.cpp 13
5278
5279 This could have meant 1 January 00:30.00 but the M will grab
5280 two digits.
5281
5282 Incorrectly specified fields of the \a string will cause an invalid
5283 QDateTime to be returned. For example, consider the following code,
5284 where the two digit year 12 is read as 1912 (see the table below for all
5285 field defaults); the resulting datetime is invalid because 23 April 1912
5286 was a Tuesday, not a Monday:
5287
5288 \snippet code/src_corelib_time_qdatetime.cpp 20
5289
5290 The correct code is:
5291
5292 \snippet code/src_corelib_time_qdatetime.cpp 21
5293
5294 \note Day and month names as well as AM/PM indicators must be given in
5295 English (C locale). If localized month and day names or localized forms of
5296 AM/PM are to be recognized, use QLocale::system().toDateTime().
5297
5298 \note If a format character is repeated more times than the longest
5299 expression in the table above using it, this part of the format will be read
5300 as several expressions with no separator between them; the longest above,
5301 possibly repeated as many times as there are copies of it, ending with a
5302 residue that may be a shorter expression. Thus \c{'tttttt'} would match
5303 \c{"Europe/BerlinEurope/Berlin"} and set the zone to Berlin time; if the
5304 datetime string contained "Europe/BerlinZ" it would "match" but produce an
5305 inconsistent result, leading to an invalid datetime.
5306
5307 \sa toString(), QDate::fromString(), QTime::fromString(),
5308 QLocale::toDateTime()
5309*/
5310
5311/*!
5312 \fn QDateTime QDateTime::fromString(QStringView string, QStringView format, QCalendar cal)
5313 \overload
5314 \since 6.0
5315*/
5316
5317/*!
5318 \overload
5319 \since 6.0
5320*/
5321QDateTime QDateTime::fromString(const QString &string, QStringView format, QCalendar cal)
5322{
5323#if QT_CONFIG(datetimeparser)
5324 QDateTime datetime;
5325
5326 QDateTimeParser dt(QMetaType::QDateTime, QDateTimeParser::FromString, cal);
5327 dt.setDefaultLocale(QLocale::c());
5328 if (dt.parseFormat(format) && (dt.fromString(string, &datetime) || !datetime.isValid()))
5329 return datetime;
5330#else
5331 Q_UNUSED(string);
5332 Q_UNUSED(format);
5333 Q_UNUSED(cal);
5334#endif
5335 return QDateTime();
5336}
5337
5338#endif // datestring

5422/*!
5423 \relates QDateTime
5424
5425 Writes \a dateTime to the \a out stream.
5426
5427 \sa {Serializing Qt Data Types}
5428*/
5429QDataStream &operator<<(QDataStream &out, const QDateTime &dateTime)
5430{
5431 QPair<QDate, QTime> dateAndTime;
5432
5433 // TODO: new version, route spec and details via QTimeZone
5434 if (out.version() >= QDataStream::Qt_5_2) {
5435
5436 // In 5.2 we switched to using Qt::TimeSpec and added offset and zone support
5437 dateAndTime = getDateTime(dateTime.d);
5438 out << dateAndTime << qint8(dateTime.timeSpec());
5439 if (dateTime.timeSpec() == Qt::OffsetFromUTC)
5440 out << qint32(dateTime.offsetFromUtc());
5441#if QT_CONFIG(timezone)
5442 else if (dateTime.timeSpec() == Qt::TimeZone)
5443 out << dateTime.timeZone();
5444#endif // timezone
5445
5446 } else if (out.version() == QDataStream::Qt_5_0) {
5447
5448 // In Qt 5.0 we incorrectly serialised all datetimes as UTC.
5449 // This approach is wrong and should not be used again; it breaks
5450 // the guarantee that a deserialised local datetime is the same time
5451 // of day, regardless of which timezone it was serialised in.
5452 dateAndTime = getDateTime((dateTime.isValid() ? dateTime.toUTC() : dateTime).d);
5453 out << dateAndTime << qint8(dateTime.timeSpec());
5454
5455 } else if (out.version() >= QDataStream::Qt_4_0) {
5456
5457 // From 4.0 to 5.1 (except 5.0) we used QDateTimePrivate::Spec
5458 dateAndTime = getDateTime(dateTime.d);
5459 out << dateAndTime;
5460 switch (dateTime.timeSpec()) {
5461 case Qt::UTC:
5462 out << (qint8)QDateTimePrivate::UTC;
5463 break;
5464 case Qt::OffsetFromUTC:
5465 out << (qint8)QDateTimePrivate::OffsetFromUTC;
5466 break;
5467 case Qt::TimeZone:
5468 out << (qint8)QDateTimePrivate::TimeZone;
5469 break;
5470 case Qt::LocalTime:
5471 out << (qint8)QDateTimePrivate::LocalUnknown;
5472 break;
5473 }
5474
5475 } else { // version < QDataStream::Qt_4_0
5476
5477 // Before 4.0 there was no TimeSpec, only Qt::LocalTime was supported
5478 dateAndTime = getDateTime(dateTime.d);
5479 out << dateAndTime;
5480
5481 }
5482
5483 return out;
5484}
5485
5486/*!
5487 \relates QDateTime
5488
5489 Reads a datetime from the stream \a in into \a dateTime.
5490
5491 \sa {Serializing Qt Data Types}
5492*/
5493
5494QDataStream &operator>>(QDataStream &in, QDateTime &dateTime)
5495{
5496 QDate dt;
5497 QTime tm;
5498 qint8 ts = 0;
5499 QTimeZone zone(QTimeZone::LocalTime);
5500
5501 if (in.version() >= QDataStream::Qt_5_2) {
5502
5503 // In 5.2 we switched to using Qt::TimeSpec and added offset and zone support
5504 in >> dt >> tm >> ts;
5505 switch (static_cast<Qt::TimeSpec>(ts)) {
5506 case Qt::UTC:
5507 zone = QTimeZone::UTC;
5508 break;
5509 case Qt::OffsetFromUTC: {
5510 qint32 offset = 0;
5511 in >> offset;
5512 zone = QTimeZone::fromSecondsAheadOfUtc(offset);
5513 break;
5514 }
5515 case Qt::LocalTime:
5516 break;
5517 case Qt::TimeZone:
5518 in >> zone;
5519 break;
5520 }
5521 dateTime = QDateTime(dt, tm, zone);
5522
5523 } else if (in.version() == QDataStream::Qt_5_0) {
5524
5525 // In Qt 5.0 we incorrectly serialised all datetimes as UTC
5526 in >> dt >> tm >> ts;
5527 dateTime = QDateTime(dt, tm, QTimeZone::UTC);
5528 if (static_cast<Qt::TimeSpec>(ts) == Qt::LocalTime)
5529 dateTime = dateTime.toTimeZone(zone);
5530
5531 } else if (in.version() >= QDataStream::Qt_4_0) {
5532
5533 // From 4.0 to 5.1 (except 5.0) we used QDateTimePrivate::Spec
5534 in >> dt >> tm >> ts;
5535 switch (static_cast<QDateTimePrivate::Spec>(ts)) {
5536 case QDateTimePrivate::OffsetFromUTC: // No offset was stored, so treat as UTC.
5537 case QDateTimePrivate::UTC:
5538 zone = QTimeZone::UTC;
5539 break;
5540 case QDateTimePrivate::TimeZone: // No zone was stored, so treat as LocalTime:
5541 case QDateTimePrivate::LocalUnknown:
5542 case QDateTimePrivate::LocalStandard:
5543 case QDateTimePrivate::LocalDST:
5544 break;
5545 }
5546 dateTime = QDateTime(dt, tm, zone);
5547
5548 } else { // version < QDataStream::Qt_4_0
5549
5550 // Before 4.0 there was no TimeSpec, only Qt::LocalTime was supported
5551 in >> dt >> tm;
5552 dateTime = QDateTime(dt, tm);
5553
5554 }
5555
5556 return in;
5557}
5558#endif // QT_NO_DATASTREAM

5618/*! \fn size_t qHash(const QDateTime &key, size_t seed = 0)
5619 \relates QHash
5620 \since 5.0
5621
5622 Returns the hash value for the \a key, using \a seed to seed the calculation.
5623*/
5624size_t qHash(const QDateTime &key, size_t seed)
5625{
5626 // Use to toMSecsSinceEpoch instead of individual qHash functions for
5627 // QDate/QTime/spec/offset because QDateTime::operator== converts both arguments
5628 // to the same timezone. If we don't, qHash would return different hashes for
5629 // two QDateTimes that are equivalent once converted to the same timezone.
5630 return key.isValid() ? qHash(key: key.toMSecsSinceEpoch(), seed) : seed;
5631}
